<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot Parliament Speaker Fails to Secure U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Parliament Speaker Sypros
Kyprianou has said in Belgrade that he failed to achieve the
release of the three American soldiers captured by Yugoslavia, the
Cyprus News Agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
Friday afternoon, Kyprianou also said that neither the U.S. nor
their allies have taken his mission seriously and Belgrade's
overriding impression is that any gesture made by them will not
achieve any results.
</P>
<P>
He expressed deep regret over his failure, adding that the
unrelentless bombings by the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO) over the past days have made his mission more difficult.
</P>
<P>
NATO began bombarding Yugoslav Serb targets on March 24 after
Milosevic refused to accept a peace agreement, which requires
Belgrade to grant autonomy to the independence-seeking Kosovo
while allowing NATO peacekeeping forces to police the province.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus and Yugoslavia have had good relations over years and
Kyprianou developed warm ties with leaders preceded Milosevic when
he was president of Cyprus from 1978 to 1988.
</P>
<P>
Kyprianou arrived in Belgrade Thursday on what he declared
"purely humanitarian mission" to seek the release of the three
U.S. soldiers, who were among the NATO troops deployed in
Macedonia and captured by Serbian forces near the
Macedonian-Yugoslav border late last month.
</P>
<P>
Kyprianou earlier in the day visited the bombed areas around
the Yugoslav capital.
</P>
<P>
The Greek air force has said it will provide Kyprianou with an
aircraft to take him back home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
