<HEADLINE> Vatican, France in Alleged Plot to Save Rwandan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The Vatican and France were trying
to save the Rwandan Bishop of Gikonongoro, Augustin Misago, who
was accused for the involvement in the Rwandan genocide in 1994,
Rwandan News Agency (RNA) reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The RNA report said since the reburial of the remains of over
20,000 Tutsis killed at Kibeho in the Rwanda genocide in 1994 in
which Augustin Misago, the Bishop of Gikongoro, was cited as a key
ring-leader, things have taken a new twist with The Vatican, and
France endeavoring to save him from justice in facilitating his
flight.
</P>
<P>
Well-informed religious sources in Kigali, capital of Rwanda,
have RNA that since Rwandan President Pasteur Bizimungu asked
Wednesday that Misago be quickly indicted and brought to book,
Misago did not return to his bishopric.
</P>
<P>
''He is hiding somewhere in Butare (in southern Rwanda),
fearing to be immediately put into custody,'' the same sources
said.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that French Ambassador to Rwanda, the Pope's
Nuncio, and the Archbishop of Kigali held a meeting to discuss
this issue on Thursday night at the French ambassador' s residence
and ended in the small hours of Friday.
</P>
<P>
''Misago is seen as a key witness of the genocide in Gikongoro,
and more particularly the crimes committed by the French troops of
the Turquoise Zone,'' said a clergyman who requested not to
disclose his name.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said there is no doubt that Bishop Misago would make
serious revelations about the role of France in condoning acts of
genocide which went on unabated after their arrival, which were
orchestrated by the '' genocidaire '' government.
</P>
<P>
Both Misago and the then Bishop of Cyangugu, Thaddee
Ntihinyurwa, now Archbishop of Kigali, were regularly flown by
French helicopters to Gisenyi, which served as the new capital of
the ''genocidaire'' government, to attend its meetings.
</P>
<P>
Also on Wednesday, genocide survivors in southwest Cyangugu
equally charged Archbishop Ntihinyurwa of active collaboration
with the armed Hutu gangs who were butchering Tutsis in his
diocese.
</P>
<P>
The two high-ranking clergymen are reportedly highly protected
by The Vatican which belatedly accepted that its servicemen and
women be brought to court and tried for their role in the killings
which claimed over half a million lives in 1994.
</P>
<P>
''There is nothing like that about Misago, I'm not aware about
any plan to help him escape justice,'' an official from the French
Embassy in Kigali, rebutted. ''What happened last night was a
reception organized by our ambassador to welcome the new Nuncio,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
During the ceremonies at Kibeho, Rwandan President Bizimungu
had emphasized the need to punish Misago, saying he is not above
the law.
</P>
<P>
Rwandan Minister of Justice Jean de Dieu Mucyo had told the
press that Misago's case file was complete, and there was nothing
still hindering his arrest and trial save that the government did
not want confrontation with his denomination.
</P>
<P>
Human rights organizations have repeatedly drawn the attention
of the Holy Seat on the Catholic Church's stubbornness to protect
its clergy people who committed crimes in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
These organizations have charged that over 20 Rwandan
''genocidaire'' priests are hiding in The Vatican.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
