<HEADLINE> Purges Go on in Rwanda's Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan parliament is shaken
by deep purges affecting nearly all parties sharing the 70 seats
of the National Transitional Assembly, the Rwanda News Agency
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Following the sacking of four parliamentarians of the
Republican Democratic Party (MDR) last month on account of alleged
crimes ranging from misconduct, incompetence, active collaboration
with the armed Hutu rebellion, to high treason, another six have
been summoned to resign within 15 days.
</P>
<P>
The request was made Thursday by the forum of political parties
under the chairmanship of Charles Muligande, the secretary general
of the Rwandan Patriotic Front (RPF).
</P>
<P>
Besides the RPF and the MDR, the forum includes the Social
Democratic Party, the Democratic Islamic Party , the Rwandan
Socialist Party, the Union for Democracy and Progress in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
One Damien Barihuta from the Christian Democratic Party, was
among the six ordered to tender their resignation or face
exclusion from their own parties.
</P>
<P>
Barihuta is said to have attempted to hit a ''cow-boy'' with a
machete. After missing the boy, the honorable parliamentarian
hit his cow with repeated machete blows.
</P>
<P>
The two parliamentarians from the Social Democratic Party have
been charged with grave misconduct. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
