<HEADLINE> Four African States Zealous about Regional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania, Malawi, Mozambique
and Zambia have reaffirmed their commitment to jointly building
the Mtwara Development Corridor, a key regional trade link.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian Minister of Works Anna Abdallah has said the country
remains serious about the initiative.
</P>
<P>
The corridor project is to build a 820-kilometer highway from
the Mtwara port on the country's southeast coast to Lake Nyasa as
a shortcut for the movement of goods for landlocked Malawi and
Zambia, and launch transportation and energy projects along the
road.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique will also benefit from the project, which is
expected to spur the economic development of its northern areas.
</P>
<P>
"Our government has no choice but to create the necessary
environment to ensure the success of this important undertaking,"
Abdallah told a meeting on the corridor Thursday in Malawi.
</P>
<P>
"I am pretty sure we shall win," media sources Friday quoted
the minister as telling delegates from the four African countries.
</P>
<P>
The minister, who is also head of the Tanzanian delegation,
said Tanzania has received inquiries and proposals on how and when
to invest in the corridor projects.
</P>
<P>
She revealed that some work has already started on the Mtwara
port on the southeastern coast of Tanzania, adding that proposals
to develop the road between Mtwara port and the Mbamba Bay on Lake
Nyasa are being studied.
</P>
<P>
Malawian Foreign Minister Mapopa Chipeta, who led his country's
 delegation, said Malawi will extend unwavering support to all
identified projects.
</P>
<P>
The four countries endorsed a proposal made by Tanzania to host
the Investors and Donors Forum in Arusha town, north Tanzania, to
solicit funds and attract investors.
</P>
<P>
Ann Dimande, head of the Mozambican delegation, said her
country will encourage people to invest in the transport
infrastructure in the corridor, adding the next inter-state
meeting on the corridor will be held in Pemba, Mozambique next
month.
</P>
<P>
Misheck Mwanza, leader of the Zambian delegation, said it is
high time the four countries worked together to harness their
resources.
</P>
<P>
The first meeting on the Mtwara Development Corridor was held
in January this year in Tanzania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
