<HEADLINE> Africa Urged to Participate in Global </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Acting Minister of
Transport and Communications Mohammed Drir said Friday that Africa
should actively participate in the global information revolution
in the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Jay Naidoo, leader of the "African
Connection Rally", who is also South African Minister of Post,
Telecommunications and Broadcasting, Mohammed said his country has
given special attention to infrastructural development to speeding
up integrated rural growth, the Ethiopian News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia supports the "African Connection Rally" for it is
aware of the significance of telecommunication, transport and
information technology to bolster the continent's trade and
investment, he said.
</P>
<P>
Naidoo said the rally is chiefly aimed at promoting investment
in the continent and redressing the unfavorable image attached to
Africa.
</P>
<P>
He said the three-week 16,000 km rally has so far covered 8,000
km to reach Ethiopia crossing Tunisia, Libya, Egypt and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Naidoo's trans-African rally set out from Bizerte, the northern
tip of African in Tunisia, to Agulhas, southern tip in South
Africa. The rally will pass 11 African states -- Tunisia, Libya,
Egypt, Sudan, Ethiopia, Kenya, Tanzania, Malawi, Zambia, Zimbabwe
and South Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
