<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Welcomes Peace Efforts by Pakistan, India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 9 (Xinhua) -- A top Chinese leader said here
on Friday that China believes the situation in South Asia is
moving in a positive direction and welcomes the recent measures
taken by Pakistan and India for the improvement of their bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng, chairman of the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress of China, was answering questions during a joint
interview with five major Pakistani media organizations.
</P>
<P>
"The situation in South Asia is moving in a positive
direction," especially after the meeting between Pakistani Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif and his Indian counterpart Atal Bihari
Vajpayee in Lahore in February this year, Li said, when answering
a question on maintenance of peace and stability in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
Li noted that the leaders of the two South Asian neighbors
indicated their willingness to resolve their disputes, including
the Kashmir issue, in a political way.
</P>
<P>
"I think that this is a good beginning," he said.
</P>
<P>
Such an expression of willingness should be followed up with
actions and concrete measures, so that the disputes could be
resolved through negotiations, he said.
</P>
<P>
Asked about what possible and necessary steps could be taken to
ensure peace and stability in the Asia Pacific region, Li said
China believed in political multipolarity and economic
globalization, which meant that world affairs should be
participated in by all countries and groups of countries rather
than are dictated by a single or a few countries.
</P>
<P>
"That is the way to ensure the peace and stability in this
region, and this is the task faced by the region," Li said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that there already existed some groups of countries in
the Asia Pacific region such as the Asia Pacific Economic
Cooperation forum, the Association of Southeast Asian Nations and
the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Li expressed the hope that these organizations would play an
increasingly important role in the process of achieving regional
peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of financial crisis, Li said: "The economic
globalization brings opportunities to countries, especially the
developing countries, but at the same time it also exposes all
countries to very great challenges." Some countries which were hit
by the financial crisis have suffered heavy losses in their
respective economies.
</P>
<P>
"So in the course of economic globalization, we have to learn
how to protect ourselves," said Li Peng.
</P>
<P>
To a question about the nuclearization in South Asia and
China's relations with Pakistan, Li stressed that China as a
signatory state to the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty and the
Non-Proliferation Treaty always honors its commitment.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Pakistan conducted its nuclear tests in May last
year after similar tests by India. "China does not support or
encourage nuclear proliferation. China does not want to see
nuclear war as it is catastrophic to the mankind," Li said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the nuclear cooperation between China and
Pakistan was confined to the area of peaceful use of nuclear
energy and such cooperation was carried out under the strict
supervision of the International Atomic Energy Agency.
</P>
<P>
Also on Friday, Li held discussions with Wasim Sajjad, chairman
of Pakistan's Senate, on the exchanges between China's NPC and the
Pakistani Senate and ways to further all-round development of
relations between the two countries. Sajjad also hosted a banquet
in honor of the Chinese leader.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng arrived here Thursday afternoon on a four-day official
visit to Pakistan at the invitation of his Pakistani counterpart
Ellahi Bukhsh Soomro.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan is the fourth leg of Li's current six-nation tour. He
has already visited Greece, Turkey and Syria, and will also tour
Bangladesh and Thailand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
