<HEADLINE> Feature: Human Body Versus Steel Bomb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KRAGUJEVAC, Yugoslavia, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Six NATO bombs
exploded right in front of thousands of Zastava employees early on
Friday wounding hundreds, of whom 126 were hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
Up in the sky NATO pilots knew there were people inside the
automobile factory complex while down on the ground Zastava
employees and their families knew that bombs were falling upon
them.
</P>
<P>
It was a combat between steel bombs and human bodies.
</P>
<P>
Ever since the onslaught of NATO bombing against the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia, employees and their families of the
Zastava Automobile Factory have been protecting, day and night,
their livelihood with their body.
</P>
<P>
The 150-year-old factory provides jobs for 38,000 people around
Kragujevac and for 60,000 more in 200 other automobile component
factories around the country.
</P>
<P>
Families and relatives included, the six bombs that exploded
inside the Kragujevac factory could affect the livelihood of
upwards of 300,000 in this country, which has a population of 1.1
million.
</P>
<P>
The bombs severely damaged the molding workshop, paint
workshop, power plant, truck assembly line and car assembly line
of the factory. More than half of the 300 hectares of the factory
were demolished within seconds right in front of the very eyes of
its employees.
</P>
<P>
Average monthly salary of Zastava employees already plummeted
from 875 Deutsch marks before international sanctions to 52 marks
at the time being.
</P>
<P>
"Has the worst already happened to us or not?" asked Milan
Beko, a chairman of the board of directors of the enterprise that
used to manufacture 235,000 automobiles a year, but now it only
managed to produce between 5,000 and 8,000 vehicles a year.
</P>
<P>
With the assistance of the Serbian government, Zastava planned
to turn out 27,000 cars this year to improve the living standards
of its employees. But....
</P>
<P>
What Zastava employees could not understand was that they
exported 165,000 Yugo cars to the United States within two years
back in 1985 and 1986. Their truck production line was a joint
venture with Italy's Iveco while their paint workshop used German
equipment and then these countries joined hands in bombing the
factory.
</P>
<P>
Beko asked that if Zastava was bombed for the fact that the
military and police use its vehicles for transport, then should
the Yugoslav farmers, bakers and tailors be bombed for feeding and
clothing the servicemen and women?
</P>
<P>
"What on earth is the world order NATO is using its Tomahawk
democracy to create for the next millenium?" he asked. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
