<DOCNO> XIE19990410.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE, France Hold Joint Military Exercises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE)
and France began joint military exercises Friday to enhance combat
abilities and readiness of the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
A military spokesman of the UAE said that the exercises,
codenamed "Gulf 1-99," will last for several days, with land, air
and naval troops involved in the first day's war games.
</P>
<P>
The unnamed spokesman said the UAE-French drills were one of a
series of exercises the UAE has decided to hold with friendly
countries this year.
</P>
<P>
The UAE-U.S. joint naval exercises, codenamed "Iron Fist 99,"
concluded last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1991 Gulf War, in which the U.S.-led alliance ended
Iraq's seven-month occupation of Kuwait, the U.S., France and
Britain have sold billions of dollars worth of arms to Gulf
countries while conducting military exercises with them to enhance
their fighting capabilities.
</P>
<P>
The UAE is especially wary of its powerful neighbor Iran, with
which it has a territorial dispute over three Gulf islands: the Abu
Mousa and the Greater and Lesser Tunbs, which are located near the
strategic shipping lanes close to the mouth of the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the UAE launched strong protest against the Iranian
naval exercises conducted near the islands. Iran flatly rejected
the protest, saying it was not wise for the UAE to condemn others
while itself was conducting military exercises frequently.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
