<HEADLINE> Nigerien PM Announces Dissolution of Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Nairobi, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Nigerien Prime Minister Ibrahim
Assane Mayaki Friday announced the dissolution of parliament and
the suspension of political activity after the sudden death of
President Ibrahim Bare Mainassara.
</P>
<P>
But the prime minister said over the state radio that the
present administration would keep in office until a national unity
government took over in the land-locked west African country.
</P>
<P>
Mainassara's death came "at a particularly grave moment in the
history of our country," Mayaki was quoted by Reuters as saying in
capital Niamey.
</P>
<P>
The political temperature rose sharply in Niamey Thursday with
an opposition call for Mainassara's resignation, which came after
the supreme court ordered poll reruns in the majority of
districts.
</P>
<P>
Vote counting in February was disrupted by violent attacks on
poll centers as the opposition appeared in the lead.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerien president was ambushed by soldiers at Niamey
Airport Friday as he was leaving for Filingue region, some 200
kilometers northeast of the capital city..
</P>
<P>
In capital Niamey itself, troops with tanks have reportedly
moved into the streets, blocking access to the presidential palace
and other key locations.
</P>
<P>
Since his election in July 1996, Mainassara had faced
relentless pressure from a militant opposition spearheaded largely
by leaders of the civilian government he overthrew in a coup
earlier that year.
</P>
<P>
Mainassara's regime has been grappling with a spate of public
service strikes which have further paralyzed the economy of the
land-locked west African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
