<HEADLINE> Lebanon's Workers to Protest Against Price Hikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The General Labor Confederation,
Lebanon's largest trade union, Friday called for sit-ins in Beirut
to protest against government's price hike policy in its 1999
budget.
</P>
<P>
The sit-ins will be held on April 21 in front of the prime
minister's palace and on the first day of the parliamentary debate
on budget bill, said a statement issued after an emergency meeting
of the 350,000-strong union. But the debate date has yet to be set.
</P>
<P>
The statement complained that the price hikes, especially the
rise on gasoline price, will impose more burdens on the middle-
and low-income classes.
</P>
<P>
It said the current government headed by Prime Minister Salim
Hoss is following suit of the previous administration of Rafik
Hariri, which received vociferous denunciations for heavy taxes
policies.
</P>
<P>
The government said the broad tax increases in the 1999 budget
endorsed Wednesday night were aimed at bringing down the deficit
to 3.37 trillion pounds (2.24 billion U.S. dollars), or about 40
percent of expenditure, from an estimated 58 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
The bill includes a rise of 2,000 pounds (about 1.3 dollars) per
20 liters on gasoline; a 104 percent tax increase on imported
liquor, 55 percent on imported beer, 35 percent on cigarette and
35 percent on flowers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
