<HEADLINE> Clinton Repeats NATO Conditions for Ceasefire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 9 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton on
Friday repeated his demand the Yugoslavia comply with all NATO
conditions before considering an end to bombing against the
country.
</P>
<P>
"NATO is determined to persist and prevail," Clinton told
reporters at the White House, repeating a refrain he has used time
and again since airstrikes began on March 24.
</P>
<P>
He said Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic must accept all
the NATO's conditions, saying he should not just comply partially
or even give "the illusion of partial compliance."
</P>
<P>
"President Milosevic must withdraw from Kosovo his military
police and paramilitary forces... He must permit deployment of an
international security force... He must allow the unconditional
return of al refugees... He must take these essential steps as we
move toward self-government and security for the people of
Kosovo," Clinton stressed.
</P>
<P>
Clinton acknowledged there has been a wave of refugees since
the NATO bombing raids against Yugoslavia. But he attributed the
responsibility not on the NATO military campaign, instead, on the
Serb resistance to the bombing.
</P>
<P>
While the Yugoslav government was convincing ethnic Albanians
into staying in their home in Kosovo, Clinton again accused
President Milosevic of blocking their "escape routes... by force."
</P>
<P>
The wave of refugees now has become a burden to U.S.-led NATO,
which was beyond alliance's expectation when starting bombing. And
Clinton has to come to do what his government could do for the
tragedy.
</P>
<P>
"A C-5 aircraft, our largest transport plane, loaded with
humanitarian daily rations header for Albanian and Macedonia, will
be stocked," he said. "Thus far, we have seen 800,000 of the 1.1
million daily rations we pledged for the region."
</P>
<P>
Clinton did not mention a Cypriot leader's mission in Belgrade
to try and obtain the release of three U.S. soldiers from the
Yugoslav government.
</P>
<P>
Belgrade has announced to hand over the three U.S. soldiers
as a condition to stop conflict in Kosovo, but has been rejected
by U.S.-led NATO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
