<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Producer Price Up by 0.2 Percent in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The producer price, which
measures prices paid by wholesalers to U.S. producers such as
factories and refineries, increased a seasonally adjusted 0.2
percent in March as energy costs jumped sharply, the Labor
Department said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The mild increase in the department's Producer Price Index for
finished goods brought the annual rate of inflation at the
wholesale level to 1.5 percent so far in 1999, compared with a
tiny 0.1 percent price decline for all of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Prices of finished energy goods jumped 1.2 percent in March,
with gasoline rising 3.5 percent, heating oil soaring 13.1 percent
-- the most in five years, residential electricity edging 0.2
percent higher and natural gas falling 1.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, energy consumers likely face even sharper price
increases in the months ahead. Crude oil jumped 27.1 percent in
March, the biggest increase since October 1990, thanks to the
recent agreement by major oil producers to cut production.
</P>
<P>
Food costs paid by wholesalers rose a moderate 0.4 percent last
month. Fruit prices fell 5.5 percent, reflecting an 18.5 percent
drop for navel oranges and 5.9 percent for golden delicious
apples.
</P>
<P>
However, vegetable prices soared 20.2 percent, the most in
eight months, reflecting increases of 115.5 percent for eggplant,
67.9 percent for corn, 67.1 percent for lettuce and 45.4 percent
for tomatoes. Fish prices jumped 9.4 percent, the largest rise in
nearly 13 years. Pork and beef rose, too.
</P>
<P>
Excluding the volatile food and energy components, the
so-called "core" producer price was unchanged in March for the
second consecutive month. That reflects pressure on domestic
producers to compete with cheaply priced imports.
</P>
<P>
Economists look to the "core" rate to discern underlying
inflation trends. After the rebound in energy costs is absorbed
over the next several months, overall price pressures should once
again become tame, they believe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
