<HEADLINE> New Water Act Gazetted In Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government gazetted
a new water act Friday which will see the development and
utilization of water resources in the southern African country.
</P>
<P>
The act will provide for the control of the use of water when
it is in short supply; the protection of the environment and the
prevention and control of water pollution.
</P>
<P>
Under the new act, no person is entitled to ownership of any
water in Zimbabwe and no water is to be stored, abstracted,
apportioned, controlled, diverted or used in any way dealt with
except in accordance with this act.
</P>
<P>
It has taken a long time for the act to be gazetted because
some commercial farmers have strongly opposed the water bill,
saying the proposed law would violate their basic rights to
privately own water resources.
</P>
<P>
Some legislators felt it was necessary to re-draft the bill to
avoid situations where the state would be faced with many legal
challenges during the implementation of the budget.
</P>
<P>
The new act replaces the Water Act of 1976, bringing to an end
the system of exclusive water rights.
</P>
<P>
Water users will participate in the management of the resources
through their representatives who shall sit in the catchment
councils to be established. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
