<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Program Becomes Seventh UN Organization to Join UNAIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
International Drug Control Program (UNDCP) has formalized its
commitment to collaboration in fighting the global HIV/AIDS
epidemic by becoming a cosponsor of the Joint United Nations
Program in HIV/AIDS (UNAIDS), a U.N. release said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
UNDCP joins the six existing UNAIDS cosponsors, the United
Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF), the United Nations Development
Program (UNDP), the United Nations Fund for Population
Activities (UNFPA), the United Nations Educational, Scientific and
Cultural Organization (UNESCO), the World Food Organization (WHO)
and the World Bank, in a coordinated effort to help the world
prevent new HIV infections, care for those already infected, and
militate the impact of the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
UNDCP addresses all aspects of he drug problem, including
demand reduction, supply reduction, legislative and institutional
advisory services to enhance governments' capacity to implement
the international drug control conventions.
</P>
<P>
UNDCP is active in supporting HIV/AIDS prevention programs
and including such components in ts own programs to reduce the
demand for illicit drugs.
</P>
<P>
Under the leadership of Executive Director Pino Arlacchi, UNDCP
operates from its headquarters in Vienna, Austria, as well as from
a field network currently comprising ten sub-regional offices and
nine country offices.  
</P>
</TEXT>
