<HEADLINE> SADC Labor Conf Opens in Swaziland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The meeting, which was opened by Swazi Prime Minister Sibusiso
Dlamini, will consider a draft SADC charter of fundamental rights,
the organizers of the meeting said.
</P>
<P>
The charter proposes to regulate and harmonize minimum
standards for the work place, including working conditions, safety
compensation, child labor, gender equality and movement of labor
throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
The 14-member SADC was established in 1992 in a bid to promote
regional cooperation. The organization consists of Angola,
Botswana, Zimbabwe, Lesotho, Malawi, Mozambique, Namibia,
Swaziland, Tanzania, Zambia, Mauritius, Democratic Republic of
Congo, Seychelles and South Africa. 
