<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Forges Energy Partnership With SADC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The Scientific and Industrial
Research and Development Center of Zimbabwe signed an agreement of
partnership with the Southern African Development Community (SADC)
Industrial Energy Management Project here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, SADC Industrial Energy Management Project
would embark on a two-year industrial energy management training
program for industrial personnel in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the program would be to enhance the ability of
industry to assess its energy to reduce costs.
</P>
<P>
The energy to be assessed would include electricity, solid
fuels, liquid fuels and water.
</P>
<P>
Director General of the Zimbabwean development center,
Christopher Chetsange said that the program would hopefully
improve energy management in the southern African country.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the industry would gain from this move as it is
looking for means of cutting on its energy bill without
sacrificing productivity," he said.
</P>
<P>
Director of the center, Mosad Emissiry told reporters that
Zimbabwe is importing about 40 percent of its energy from
Mozambique and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
He said the country's energy management is very low and needs
to be supported by all stake-holders.
</P>
<P>
"Any effort to serve energy should be supported to cut on the
importation of energy and the huge bills the country has to pay,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
