<HEADLINE> 3 Americans Further Remanded in Harare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Suspected American saboteurs Garry
Blanchard, Joseph Pettijohn and John Dixon appeared before a
Harare magistrate court on Friday for the third time and were
further remanded in custody to April 23.
</P>
<P>
No reasons for the remand were given, the Zimbabwe News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Counsel for defense Jerremy Callow made fresh submissions that
the Americans were severely tortured and subjected to inhuman
treatment by investigating officers at Chikurubi Maximum Prison in
Harare, the agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Callow said they had electric shocks applied to their genitals,
suffered physical assaults and had been threatened with death.
</P>
<P>
The Americans are being charged with violating sections of the
Law and Order Act, being involved in acts of sabotage and unlawful
possession of arms of war.
</P>
<P>
They were arrested on March 7 at Harare International Airport
while they attempted to board a Swissair flight to the United
States via Zurich, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
Among the arms of war found in their possession were AK-47
rifles, shotguns, pistons and knives. 
</P>
