<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerien PM Confirms Assasination of President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Nairobi, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Nigerien President President
Ibrahim Bare Mainassara was killed at Niamey Airport Friday,
Nigerien Prime Minister Ibrahim Assane Mayaki confirmed.
</P>
<P>
Mayaki announced Mainassara's death on the state radio, Reuters
said in a report from the Nigerien capital Niamey.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister was quoted as saying that the president had
been killed in an "unfortunate accident."
</P>
<P>
The report said that soldiers fired on the president in an
ambush at the airport as Mainassara was said to have left for
Filingue region, about 200 kilometers northeast of the capital
city.
</P>
<P>
In capital Niamey itself, troops with tanks have reportedly
moved into the streets, blocking access to the presidential palace
and other key locations.
</P>
<P>
The political temperature rose sharply in Niamey Thursday with
an opposition call for his resignation, which came after the
supreme court ordered poll reruns in the majority of districts.
</P>
<P>
Vote counting in February was disrupted by violent attacks on
poll centers as the opposition appeared in the lead.
</P>
<P>
Since his election in July 1996, Mainassara had faced
relentless pressure from a militant opposition spearheaded largely
by leaders of the civilian government he overthrew in a coup
earlier that year.
</P>
<P>
Mainassara's regime has been grappling with a spate of public
service strikes which have further paralyzed the economy of the
land-locked west African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
