<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel to Reduce Troops in S. Lebanon: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister Moshe
Arens said on Friday that he will propose to the government to
reduce the number of Israel Defense Force (IDF) in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
During an interview with Israel television channel one, Arens
said he has this idea for some time and is thinking about to
reduce the IDF number in the security zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The IDF will continue to transfer some of the IDF outposts
into the hands of the South Lebanese Army (SLA) inside the
security zone, through which the number of the IDF soliders could
be reduced, he said.
</P>
<P>
Till now, he said, about 70 percent of the military outposts
inside the security zone have already been transferred into the
hands of the SLA and the IDF will hand over more to them.
</P>
<P>
Transferring more outposts to the SLA can help reduce the IDF
numbers and by this way it could help prevent more casualties of
the IDF in the security zone, he said.
</P>
<P>
Anyway, he added, this does not mean that Israel is to
withdraw its troops from the security zone.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up the security zone in south Lebanon in 1985 with
a self-claimed purpose of protecting its northern security.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese military groups such as Hezbollah have been waging
military resistance against the IDF since then.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
