<HEADLINE> Security Council Urges End to Hostilities in Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Friday unanimously adopted a resolution demanding "an immediate
halt to the hostilities" in the Democratic Republic of the Congo
and calling for "the immediate signing of a cease-fire agreement
allowing the orderly withdrawal of all foreign forces."
</P>
<P>
The Security Council "welcomes the intention of the Government
of the Democratic Republic of the Congo to hold an all-inclusive
national debate as a precursor to elections, and encourages
further progress in this regard," said the resolution.
</P>
<P>
The resolution condemns all massacres carried out on the
territory of the Congo (K) and "calls for an international
investigation into all events, including those in the province of
South Kivu and other atrocities," the resolution said.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council slammed "the continuing activity of and
support to all armed groups" in the country, the resolution said.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council expressed its support for the regional
mediation process by the Organization of African Unity and the
Southern African Development Community to find a peaceful
settlement of the conflict in the Congo (K) and called on the
international community to continue to support these efforts, the
resolution said.
</P>
<P>
The presidents of Angola, Namibia and Zimbabwe Thursday
recommitted themselves to helping their ally President Laurent
Kabila fight a rebellion in the Congo (K).
</P>
<P>
After two days of talks in the Angolan capital of Luanda which
some analysts had thought might produce a cease-fire proposal, the
leaders said that they would continue to provide assistance to the
embattled Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, Namibia and Angola sent troops and military equipment
to the Congo (K) last August to help Kabila fight a rebellion
backed by Uganda and Rwanda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
