<HEADLINE> Mexico, Canada Advance Toward Strategic Alliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Mexico and Canada march toward
a strategic alliance, Mexican President President Ernesto Zedillo
said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Zedillo said this at the official welcoming ceremony for
Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien in the center of the capital
city, which happens to occur during the 55th anniversary of the
formal establishment of diplomatic relations between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The Mexican President expressed his satisfaction at the fifth
anniversary of the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA)
implementation.
</P>
<P>
Zedillo highlighted the benefit brought by NAFTA to the two
countries, saying that five years after the signing of the
agreement, trade exchanges between Mexico and Canada grew 80
percent.
</P>
<P>
"Mexicans feel very proud of their relation with Canada,
because it is founded on mutual respect and a firm friendship, in
growing affinities and in the search for reciprocal benefits,"
said Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
He said that Chretien's visit will strengthen the constructive
dialogue between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Chretien praised NAFTA, stressing that the courageous decision
taken five years ago has given a bigger sense of common interests
and purposes for the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He added that the relation with Mexico has taken an upward road
and encompasses all the government activities, and at the same
time involves entrepreneurs of the two countries in different
sectors of production.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian Prime Minister said that he will analyze with
President Zedillo the new directions to be taken to maintain that
impulse.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian Premier Arrived in this capital Thursday night for
a three-day official visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
