<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab League Raps Israeli Acts Against Palestinians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League Friday denounced
Israel's aggressive practices against the Palestinian people,
asserting that such acts contradict international laws.
</P>
<P>
The league made the denunciation in a statement marking the
Deir Yassin massacre perpetrated by Zionist gangs against the
Palestinians on April 9, 1947.
</P>
<P>
The league said the Israeli onslaught against the Palestinians
was continuing in an attempt to get rid of the Arab presence in
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The statement underlined that all the abhorrent and racist
practices by Israel will not undermine the Palestinian people's
steadfastedness on their rights, including setting up an
independent state with Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
But Israel maintains that Jerusalem is its "undivided and
eternal capital" and is taking steps to judaize the holy city.
</P>
<P>
The statement urged the world community to curb the current
practices of the Israeli government and counter its Zionist policy
based on driving Palestinian inhabitants out of their land so as
to build Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
The statement also lauded the stance adopted by the European
Union (EU), which voiced its clear support for the Palestinians'
rights to self-determination.
</P>
<P>
The EU issued a statement last month, saying that the
Palestinians have "unqualified right to self-determination,
including the option of a state."
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat has threatened to declare an
independent state on May 4 when the five-year interim self-rule
period enshrined in Oslo accords expires.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is on a global campaign to rally international support
for the plan and recognition for the future Palestinian state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990410.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Coffee Production to Be Up by 70 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's coffee production is
anticipated to increase by 70 percent this year reaching 53,000
tons from 31,177 tons of last year, the Coffee Board of Kenya said
here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Ndamduki, an official with the marketing department of
the Coffee Board, said that Kenya had 26,946 tons of clean coffee
ready for marketing and 21,750 tons of unmilled coffee, and the
country's five major commercial millers had by March received
bookings for 4,342 tons of coffee.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Planters Co-operative Union, the country's leading
coffee miller, projects to receive 41,584 tons of coffee this year
compared to 22, 745 tons in 1998. The union now has a stock of
17,927 tons of clean coffee and 17,530 tons of unmilled coffee.
</P>
<P>
Socfinaf, another major mill in the east African country, is
expected to receive 6,821 tons of coffee as against 5,209 tons
last year. Currently it has in its stores 5,246 tons of clean
coffee and 642 tons of unmilled coffee.
</P>
<P>
Thika Coffee Mills plans to mill 3,678 tons in 1999 compared to
2,341 tons last year. It now has in its stores 1,449 tons of
milled coffee and 1, 920 tons of unmilled coffee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
