<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, April 10 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Aslan Maskhadov, president of Russia's Chechen
Republic, escaped another assassination attempt on Saturday, the
second in three weeks, a Chechen official said.
</P>
<P>
Chechen security forces defused a bomb discovered along the way
that Maskhadov was to drive to a gathering of supporters at Stary
Atagi, a village south of the Chechen capital, Grozny. The
president later made the trip safely, said the official from the
Chechen Security Ministry.
</P>
<P>
On March 21, Maskhadov narrowly escaped assassination when a
bomb exploded near his motorcade in Grozny.
</P>
<P>
Maskhadov, who used to be the leader of the Chechen separatists
during the 1994-96 war with the Russian Federation in Chechnya,
became the president of the republic in February 1997. (Russia-
Chechnya-Assassination)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji and U.S. President
Bill Clinton issued here Saturday a joint statement on China's
accession to the World Trade Organization (WTO), stressing the
importance of continued efforts by China and the U.S. toward
China's early WTO entry.
</P>
<P>
The statement said Premier Zhu and President Clinton reaffirmed
that the United States and China have advanced substantially their
common goal of China's accession to the WTO.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also signed an agreement on U.S.-China
agricultural cooperation earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the two countries signed a protocol to the agreement
relating to civil air transport.
</P>
<P>
"This Agreement and the significant consensus achieved on a
board range of market access and Protocol issues have further
advanced that goal," it said, "President Clinton and Premier Zhu
welcome this significant progress."
</P>
<P>
"The United States strongly supports the accession of the
People's Republic of China to the WTO in 1999," the statement
noted. (US-China-WTO)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin made a phone call to
Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema Saturday to reiterate
Russia's strong opposition to the airstrikes against Yugoslavia by
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) , the presidential
press office said.
</P>
<P>
In the phone conversation which was arranged at the request of
D'Alema, Yeltsin expressed his displeasure over NATO's action. But
the press office declined to disclose any details.
</P>
<P>
Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov also called D'Alema on
the same day to stress Moscow's opposition to the strikes.
</P>
<P>
Primakov told D'Alema Russia's "extremely negative assessment
of the actions of the (NATO) alliance that have only complicated
the efforts to search for a political solution... and caused a
dramatic deterioration of the humanitarian situation in the
province (of Kosovo)," Primakov's spokeswoman Tatyana Aristarkhova
said. (Russia-Italy-Kosovo) 
</P>
</TEXT>
