<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IRA Rejects Peace Declaration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The Irish Republican Army (IRA)
confirmed on Saturday its rejection of last week's draft
declaration on the Good Friday Agreement.
</P>
<P>
Senior representatives said they were "unimpressed" by the
efforts of British and Irish Governments to advance the Northern
Ireland peace process, according to BBC report.
</P>
<P>
The news is a serious blow to hopes of achieving a breakthrough
on the thorny issue of arms decomissioning when talks resume on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
IRA personnel told journalists in briefings that the draft
document drawn up after marathon multi-party talks at
Hillsborough, near Belfast, showed the two governments failed to
address the Ulster Unionist "veto" on progress in the peace accord
and had caused anger among republicans.
</P>
<P>
IRA's political wing Sinn Fein has rejected the peace
declaration, saying it has had "massive change" to the peace
agreement signed a year ago and was unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
The peace declaration said decommissioning of IRA and other
terrorist arms was not a condition for the entry of Sinn Fein into
a power-sharing executive of a new assembly. But it stated that
there was an obligation to hand over weapons to meet the
requirements of last year's peace accord. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
