<DOCNO> XIE19990410.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smile and Surprise: Chinese Audience Come Across New Curies in French Comedy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Chinese theatergoers attending
the Friday night Chang'an Theater presentation of a new French
comedy exhibited both surprise and amusement at the new face
portrayed for highly-respected Nobel Prize winners Pierre and
Marie Curie.
</P>
<P>
"My generation worships scientists, especially prestigious
scientists like the Curies," said a middle-aged medical school
professor, adding that "I was quite frankly pleased with the new
face of the seemingly familiar scientists and was shocked by the
jokes and innuendoes."
</P>
<P>
Two students from the Beijing Broadcast Institute praised the
comical effect, but nonetheless voiced their disapproval of the "
depiction" of the scientists whom they studied and learned to
respect.
</P>
<P>
Playwright Jean-Noel Fenwick flew to Beijing to see his comedy -
- The Palm of Mr. Shutz -- staged in China, the 18th country to
stage the comedy.
</P>
<P>
Fenwick, a literature major and journalist, entered the ranks
of professional authors in 1988. His first drama -- The Palm of Mr.
Schutz -- won 11 nominations and won four French Moliere Awards in
1990.
</P>
<P>
Fenwick said his goal was to offer audiences a fresh
perspective enabling them to observe the lives of the renowned
scientists. He proceeded on the basis of historical and scientific
fact, and used brave artistic exaggerations for comedy.
</P>
<P>
French ambassador to China Pierre Morel sent a letter of
congratulations to the Chinese cast and commented that the
dramatist disclosed the complexities of human nature in the
scientific community. The ultimate purpose of scientific research
failed to hinder the Curies' enjoyment of life, including the
beauty of nature, and both their enthusiasm for work and mutual
love.
</P>
<P>
Wei Xiaoping translated and directed the comedy staged with a
cast from the China National Youth Theater. Wei said Chinese
scientists requested that he avoid following the old path of
stereotyping them as scientific geniuses and idiots of life.
</P>
<P>
"Maintaining a balance between the humanity of scientific
saints and considering the acceptability of traditional viewers is
very much like dancing in chains," said Wei.
</P>
<P>
Ding Jiali, the recipient of a series of national drama and
movie awards, cited her role as Marie Curie as an ultimate
challenge.
</P>
<P>
"I totally rejected the new image of Marie. However, reading
biographies vividly opened my eyes to a wise, lovely, humorous and
even naughty Marie, and I simply accepted the challenge," said
Ding.
</P>
<P>
"The conflict between the purity of science and the vanity of
authority, as well as the inconsistency between lofty ideals and
harsh reality in the play reflect our lives, and lead us to
meditation after laughter," said Producer Luo Dajun.
</P>
<P>
"The Curies wear stiff face, while mine is wild and cheerful,"
said Fenwick, adding that "the true Curies are between the two
dimensions."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990410.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Military Vows to Avenge Its Deputy Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Islamic Revolutionary
Guards Corps (IRGC) Saturday vowed to avenge the killing of
Brigadier General Ali Sayyad Shirazi, deputy chief of the joint
staff of the Iranian armed force.
</P>
<P>
Expressing condolence to Shirazi's family, Commander of IRGC
Rahim Safavi said under the command of the Iranian supreme leader
Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, the IRGC and the army are ready to counter
any plot of the enemies, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Shirazi was killed at 0645 hours local time (0215 GMT) in
northern Tehran as he left home for work, the agency said. It gave
no details.
</P>
<P>
The Iraq-based Iranian opposition MKO has claimed responsibility
for the assassination.
</P>
<P>
The armed opposition group said that Shirazi was targeted
because he was responsible for purging and executing military
personnel and the death of hundreds of thousands of teenagers in
the Iraqi-Iranian war from 1980 to 1988.
</P>
<P>
Shirazi, born in 1944, served as commander of the Iranian
army's land force during the Iranian-Iraqi war.
</P>
<P>
The MKO has claimed responsibility for several assassinations
in Iran, including the killing last August of Assadollah
Lajevardi, the former head of Iran's Prisons Organization.
</P>
<P>
The MKO had fought against the former Iranian shah regime, but
was outlawed in 1981 due to sharp difference with the then Iranian
government.
</P>
<P>
It has since launched a series of attacks on Iranian interests
inside and outside Iran. In retaliation, the Iranian armed forces
also bombed the MKO bases in Iraq several times.
</P>
<P>
Following Shirazi's assassination, senior Iranian leaders,
including President Mohammad Khatami, Chairman of the State
Expediency Council Hashemi Rafsanjani and Majlis (parliament)
Speaker Nateq Nouri, issued condolence messages over the killing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
