<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wild Siberian Tiger Population Drops in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Wildlife experts said today that
less than 20 Siberian tigers currently live in the wild in China
due to deteriorating ecological environment
</P>
<P>
The population figure was reached following a two-month joint
investigation by wildlife experts from China, the United States
and Russia.
</P>
<P>
The investigation, carried out between January 16 and the end
of March, covered major tiger habitats in Heilongjiang and Jilin
provinces, northeast China. Extensive information was obtained by
tracing tiger footprints and interviewing eyewitnesses.
</P>
<P>
Guan Guosheng, a representative of the Heilongjiang Wild Animal
Research Institute, said the province has only five to eight wild
Siberian tigers, with an additional 10-odd animals living in the
wild in neighboring Jilin.
</P>
<P>
"Heilongjiang and Jilin were home to some 20-30 wild tigers in
the early 1990s, down substantially from the 80-odd tigers some 20
years ago in Heilongjiang alone," said Guan.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the deteriorating environment mainly caused by
extensive felling of trees is to blame for the rapid decrease.
</P>
<P>
China plans to introduce a comprehensive plan to protect
natural forests in northeast China and will demarcate wild tiger
protection zones in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Siberian tigers, one of the world's most endangered species,
are dispersed in natural habitats in Siberia and northeast China.
Chinese zoos currently house some 100-odd such animals.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
