<HEADLINE>   Olympic Champion Sun Loses in National Judos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, Guangxi, Southwestern China, April 10 (Xinhua) --
Olympic champion Sun Fuming lost a close fight to Zhang Qingfang
in the final of the over-78-kilogram category on the first-day of
the Chinese national women's judo championships here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
It was also a dismal day for Asian Games champion Yuan Hua,
heavyweight champion in the Bangkok Games, lost to Sun to finish
third and other Asiad gold medalists Tang Lin and Wang Xianbo also
finished with bronze medals in the light-heavyweight and
welterweight classed, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Yin Yufeng from Jiangsu Province beat Tang Lin en route to win
the under-78kg class while Sun Xiaofang from Liaoning Province
took the 63kg grade title.
</P>
<P>
The 70kg gold medal went to Liaoning's Qin Dongya.
</P>
<P>
The national championships served as the second stop of a three-
leg qualifying series, which was set up to select the national
squad for the world championships in Britain in October.
</P>
<P>
Sun, who won the heavyweight title in the 1996 Atlanta Olympics,
got a koka penalty at the start of the bout, and did not overcome
the points deficit afterward to her Henan Province's opponent,
whom she beat on an ippon score in the final of the first stop of
the qualifying series in Beijing less a month ago.
</P>
<P>
"I'm just too busy with my heavy schedule," said Sun, who just
returned home from a 15-day European competitions tour. "I cannot
keep up my best form."
</P>
<P>
The 57kg, 52kg and under-48kg competitions will be held on
Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
