<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Leaves Washington for Denver </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji
left here Saturday for Denver to continue his official visit in
the United States, after achieving significant progress with the U.
S. side on China's entry into the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
Before leaving Washington for Denver, the third stop of his U.S.
trip, the Chinese Premier issued a joint statement with U.S.
President Bill Clinton concerning China's entry into the WTO, in
which the United States expressed its strong support for the
accession of China to the WTO in 1999.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, the two leaders reaffirmed that the two
countries have advanced substantially their common goal of China's
accession to the WTO.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also signed an agreement on U.S.-China
agricultural cooperation earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the two countries signed a protocol to the agreement
relating to civil air transport.
</P>
<P>
"This agreement and the significant consensus achieved on a
broad range of market access and Protocol issues have further
advanced that goal," said the Joint Statement.
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhu and President Clinton have instructed their trade
ministers to continue bilateral negotiations in order to
satisfactorily resolve the important remaining issues and reach
agreement on strong commercial terms as soon as possible,
according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
Zhu, who is the first Chinese premier to visit the United
States in 15 years, arrived in Los Angeles on April 6 for the
official visit to the United States.
</P>
<P>
During his three-day stay in Washington, Zhu exchanged views
with President Clinton and other American leaders on China-U.S.
relations as well as international and regional issues of common
concern.
</P>
<P>
He also co-chaired with U.S. Vice President Al Gore the second
session of China-U.S. Forum on Environment and Development.
</P>
</TEXT>
