<HEADLINE> Mozambican Elections to Be Held This Year: Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Manuel Tome, Secretary General of
the ruling Mozambican Liberation Front (Frelimo), said his party
insisted that the general elections be held this year as planned.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Tome said that preparations,
like the formation of the National Electoral Commission recently,
went ahead well, the Noticias daily reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Tome said that he is fully confident of the electoral
commission, saying he believe that the the elections will go
smoothly under the leadership of the commission.
</P>
<P>
The specific date of the elections can be adjusted with the
framework of electoral laws, but should definitely be held within
this year, and by no means be postponed, Tome said.
</P>
<P>
The government and parliament are operating normally, Tome
said, any postponement, as rumored by some western powers and
opposition parties, will force the president to have a care-taker
government, which is not necessary.
</P>
<P>
Tome said the ruling Frelimo party has created every condition
to win in the coming elections, citing the fast development of the
country's economy as one of the very important conditions for its
victory.
</P>
<P>
The last election was held in late October, 1994 when Frelimo
won 129 out of 250 parliamentary seats, with Joaquim Chissano
being elected as the President. 
</P>
