<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Comply With OPEC Oil Quotas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian oil companies have been
directed to reduce the volume of April cargoes and to be in full
compliance with the recent OPEC decision on oil production
curtailment beginning from next month.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the Nigerian National Petroleum
Corporation (NNPC) said that Nigeria's crude oil production will
be reduced from 2.033 million barrels per day (bpd) to 1.885
million bpd starting from May, the Tribune newspaper reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, the reduction of all April cargoes
between five and seven percent by all crude oil producing
companies in Nigeria is a first step toward full compliance with
the OPEC decision.
</P>
<P>
Allocation of production quotas for May 1999 have been made to
reflect full compliance with the 1.885 million bpd quotas given
to Nigeria which is the sixth largest oil producer in the world.
</P>
<P>
The statement noted that "the NNPC wishes to express Nigeria's
 commitment to full compliance with the OPEC curtailment of crude
oil production as it affects Nigeria from 2.033 to 1.885 million
barrels per day." 
</P>
