<HEADLINE> Sandstorm Sweeps Through Northwest China Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 10 (Xinhua) -- A sandstorm swept through the
drought-stricken Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region in northwest China
this morning.
</P>
<P>
The Ningxia capital of Yinchuan was covered with thick layer of
fine sand and dust and local residents venturing on the streets
were forced to cover faces to protect themselves from the sandy
gale descending from the yellowish sky.
</P>
<P>
The storm lasted several hours and the visibility in Yinchuan,
Yongning, Helan and Qingtongxia dropped to about 800 meters.
</P>
<P>
The northern part of Ningxia has reeled in the midst of a 200-
day drought since last September. Temperature have been 2.5
degrees centigrade higher than normal since April. The searing sun
has turn the top 30 centimeters of soil into dry powder in some
counties, including Yanchi and Tongxin.
</P>
<P>
Cold fronts from Mongolia collided with strong southern gales
circulating above deserts circling northern parts of the region
this morning, creating the sandstorm.
</P>
<P>
Ningxia experiences frequent droughts, with resulting
sandstorms blowing as far east as to Beijing, the Chinese capital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
