<HEADLINE> $28.5m Allocated for Easing Water Shortage in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia's Harari State
announced Saturday that some 28.5 million U.S. dollars has been
allocated for potable water development projects to be undertaken
in the south-eastern Ethiopian town of Harar in five years.
</P>
<P>
Harar, capital of the Harari State, is one of the serious water
shortage towns in Ethiopia. The water currently supplied to the
town per day is less than half of the 6,897 cubic meters daily
water need of the town.
</P>
<P>
According to the state water, mines and energy bureau, the
five-year water development project is aimed at alleviating water
shortage in the town.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed Kelif, head of the water development department of the
bureau, was quoted by the Ethiopian News Agency as saying that the
sinking of over 10 deep water wells around Dire Jara has already
been completed.
</P>
<P>
He said 3.16 million U.S. dollars has been earmarked for the
water projects being carried out in Harar this year. 
