<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Enjoys More Monetary Autonomy After Handover: Yam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong enjoys a higher
degree of monetary autonomy after it became a special
administrative region of China on July 1, 1998, Joseph Yam, chief
executive of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA), said here
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Since the establishment of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR), its monetary relationship with China's mainland has
been handled strictly in accordance with the "one country, two
systems" principle, Yam noted in a speech at a symposium in
commemoration of the ninth anniversary of the promulgation of the
Basic Law of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Yam said the legal protection offered by the Basic Law, the
constitutional instrument of the HKSAR, has, to a very great
extent, contributed to Hong Kong's monetary stability during the
political transition and has enabled Hong Kong to withstand the
severe challenges brought about by the unprecedented financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law provides that the HKSAR government shall, on its
own, formulate monetary and financial policies to maintain the
status of Hong Kong as an international financial center, Yam said.
</P>
<P>
"The high level of monetary autonomy enjoyed by Hong Kong, as
provided in the Basic Law and the monetary legislation, is not
just something written into laws, it is also realized in our
actual implementation of monetary policies," Yam stressed.
</P>
<P>
The financial turmoil that erupted just after the transfer of
government has subjected Hong Kong's monetary autonomy to a
rigorous testing, he said.
</P>
<P>
When the HK dollar and the financial markets were under great
pressure and the economic and monetary conditions were extremely
difficult, all the measures to address the financial crisis,
including the market operation undertaken last August for the
purpose of preserving order in Hong Kong's financial markets, were
entirely formulated by the government of the HKSAR on its own, he
said.
</P>
<P>
During this period of financial turmoil, the central government
has strictly adhered to the provisions of the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
The central government has shown confidence in the ability of
the HKSAR government and has not interfered in Hong Kong's
monetary affairs, Yam said.
</P>
<P>
The success of the HKSAR government in addressing the financial
turmoil has fully demonstrated the effectiveness of "Hong Kong
people ruling Hong Kong," he added.
</P>
<P>
An issue related to monetary autonomy is the handling of the
monetary relationship between Hong Kong and the mainland under the
"one country, two systems" principle, especially given that the
economic relationship between the two places has become
increasingly close, Yam said.
</P>
<P>
The relationship can be best summarized as "one country, two
currencies, two monetary systems and two mutually independent
monetary authorities."
</P>
<P>
Financial business between the mainland and Hong Kong is
treated as international financial affairs and conducted in
accordance with the rules and practices of international financial
activities, Yam said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong continues its participation in international
financial activities in accordance with the provisions of the
Basic Law, which provides that the HKSAR may, using the name of "
Hong Kong, China," maintain and develop financial ties with
different countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
Following the handover, Hong Kong has become even more active
in the international financial scene, Yam noted.
</P>
<P>
In addition to further developing cooperation with regional
central banks, the HKMA has strengthened its ties with
multilateral and international financial institutions such as the
International Monetary Fund and the World Bank and the Bank for
International Settlements, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
