<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agassi, Becker in Hong Kong Open Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Third seed Andre Agassi of the
United States outplayed Hendrik Dreekmann of Germany in straight
sets here Saturday to join veteran German player Boris Becker in
the final of Salem Hong Kong Open.
</P>
<P>
Agassi, the only non-German player in the semi-finals, overcame
an early deficit to beat Dreekmann, who eliminated American
Michael Chang and top seed Richard Krajicek of the Netherlands, 6-
3, 6-0 in 48 minutes.
</P>
<P>
After losing his first game in the opening set, Agassi, who
conceded no more than three games in every set he played in the
tournament, found rhythm and broke back to level the score quickly.
</P>
<P>
Dreekmann seemed to have lost confidence when he led 40-0 but
was broken by swift Agassi in his first game of the second set.
Agassi then served three aces in the next game to make it 3-0 and
broke a slackened Dreekmann twice again to win the match.
</P>
<P>
Agassi said he did not find rhythm right away at the beginning
of the match but gradually got comfortable with his serves and
shots. "I focused quickly and took every point seriously," he said.
</P>
<P>
Confirming a report about his planning of divorce with actress
Brook Shields, the former world No.1 said he has come to Hong Kong
simply because he "needs to play more tennis."
</P>
<P>
Agassi, now having a chance to win his first title of the year,
said he felt good both physically and mentally.
</P>
<P>
Dreekmann said he had two chances in the first set but Agassi
played so fast and "there's no much to do like that."
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old and 98th-ranked German, who started to cheer
himself up after a nice shot in the last part of the match, said
he was satisfied with his performance since he had beaten such
strong players as Krajicek and Chang.
</P>
<P>
He said the Hong Kong Open gave him confidence and he is "
looking forward to Tokyo (Japan Open)."
</P>
<P>
In the other semi-final match, experiences helped Becker to
defeat countryman Bernd Karbacher 6-4, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Karbacher seemed to be unstoppable on his way to the semifinal
as the 31-year-old ousted No. 2 seed Patrick Rafter in the first
round and seventh seed Jonas Bjorkman in the quarter-final.
</P>
<P>
Becker, seeking his 50th career title, anticipated the final
with in-form Agassi a "50-50" match, saying he is now enjoying
tennis and is doing his best to play rather than caring too much
about the title. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
