<HEADLINE> Arafat Seeks India's Support for Palestine Statehood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian President Yasser
Arafat held wide-ranging discussions with Indian leaders Saturday,
and sought India's support for the creation of an independent
Palestine state by next month.
</P>
<P>
An official of the External Affairs Ministry said Arafat
exchanged views with Indian President Kocheril Raman Narayanan and
Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee on regional and international
issues of mutual interest including the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived here late Friday night on a one-day working
visit as part of his tour to gauge international opinion on
declaring Palestine an independent state.
</P>
<P>
The Press Trust of India (PTI) quoted a Palestinian embassy
official as saying that the Palestinian leader consulted Indian
leaders for their support of his plan to declare Palestine an
independent state in May.
</P>
<P>
India has over the years extended full support to Palestine's
cause of independence.
</P>
<P>
During their 40-minute meeting, Arafat and Narayanan also
discussed NATO's military action against Yugoslavia, official
sources said.
</P>
<P>
India urged NATO to immediately stop its unilateral military
action against Yugoslavia, stressing that the present crisis in
Kosovo could only be resolved through peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
Arafat also met Arab diplomats in New Delhi. He is scheduled to
visit Pakistan and have a stopover in Yemen before going to China.
</P>
<P>
Before coming here, Arafat had visited a number of countries
including Turkey, Jordan, Russia, Japan, Vietnam, Indonesia and
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said Friday in Dhaka, Bangladesh, that he would visit
more countries to hold consultations with world leaders on his
plan to declare an independent state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
