<HEADLINE> Tarim Oil Field Ranks Eighth Largest in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The Tarim Oil Field in northwest
China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region has emerged as the
country's eighth largest crude oil and natural gas producer.
</P>
<P>
Today marks the 10th anniversary of oil and gas exploration and
exploitation at the Tarim Oil Field which is located in the Tarim
Basin in southern Xinjiang. More than 20,000 skilled personnel and
workers have participated in developing the field over the past
decade.
</P>
<P>
"The field has produced some 20 million tons of crude oil and
more than three billion cu.m. of natural gas, with total revenues
surpassing 3.44 billion yuan," according to Liao Yongyuan,
director of the Tarim Oil Exploration and Exploitation
Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The field has an annual crude oil production capacity of five
million tons, with actual annual production hitting 4.2 million
tons in 1997. The figure represented a dramatic increase compared
with the 34,000 tons produced in 1989.
</P>
<P>
Liao said "the field has maintained a stable production, with
the daily average output of each well reaching 80 tons, 16 times
the national average."
</P>
<P>
Chinese geologists have discovered that the Tarim Basin, an
area about the same size as France, has 10.8 billion tons in
petroleum reserves, as well as 8.4 trillion cu.m. of natural gas.
The area is reputed as the "Ocean of Hope" for China's petroleum
industry.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
