<HEADLINE> Philippine Army Sgt. to Be Freed Sunday: Senator </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Army Sgt. Alipio
Lozada, abducted by the New People's Army (NPA) on March 5, is set
to be released by the rebels in Mindanao Sunday, Philippine News
Agency quoted Senator Legarda as saying Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Legarda, who had helped broker the successful release on Friday
of Police Chief Inspector Roberto Bernal in Sorsogon, said Lozada
would likely be released in Caraga region.
</P>
<P>
Lozada is being held captive by the NPA in Surigao del Sur.
</P>
<P>
Legarda expressed confidence that Lozada's safe and orderly
release would push through, "assuming that conditions favor such."
</P>
<P>
"If the military and police forces in Surigao del Sur will
exercise as much self-restraint and discipline as the government
troops in Albay and Sorsogon, where Bernal was released, then we
see no reason why Lozada's release should be aborted," Legarda
said.
</P>
<P>
Legarda stressed the need for the rebels to complete the
release of all the four military officers on or before their
self-imposed April 19 deadline.
</P>
<P>
"This would create a lot of goodwill between the rebels and the
government and guarantee the resumption of the stalled peace
negotiations," Legarda said.
</P>
<P>
The rebels abducted and took hostage four military and police
officers during the past two months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
