<HEADLINE> German Envoy Arrives, Khatami Invited for Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 10 (Xinhua) -- A German special envoy arrived
here Saturday morning to submit an official invitation from
German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder to his Iranian counterpart
Mohammad Khatami to visit Germany.
</P>
<P>
Bodo Hombach, head of the Federal Chancellery, arrived here
after the Iranian judiciary on Thursday granted a release on bail
to German businessman Helmut Hofer, who had been sentenced to
death for having "illegal sexual relations" with an Iranian Muslim
woman.
</P>
<P>
Last November, Hombach was appointed as Schroeder's special
envoy in charge of the Hofer case.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival, the German envoy said that the governments of
Iran and Germany are doing their best to improve bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
"We are determined to break all the barriers and the time has
come now to have another start for expanding our ties," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hombach said his visit aims at strengthening economic and
cultural ties between the two countries and the two governments
are determined to cement their ties in all fields.
</P>
<P>
Germany has been Iran's biggest trading partner. However,
bilateral ties were strained in April, 1997 after a Berlin court
accused Iranian leaders of sponsoring terrorist assassinations
against Iranian dissidents in Germany.
</P>
<P>
A possible rapprochement between the two sides was then blocked
by the death sentence on the German businessman.
</P>
<P>
Hofer was arrested in September, 1997 at Tehran international
airport together with an Iranian woman who was waiting for him,
upon his arrival from Germany. He was then sentenced to death by a
local court in Tehran in January, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Under Iranian law, non-Muslim men are forbidden from having any
sexual relations with Muslim women.
</P>
<P>
Hofer appealed the court ruling by claiming that he had
converted to Islam before meeting the Iranian woman. And Bonn has
repeatedly called on Tehran to release Hofer.
</P>
<P>
The 57-year-old businessman reportedly would be delivered to
the German envoy during his visit.
</P>
<P>
However, an Iranian judicial spokesman said on Thursday that
Hofer would not be allowed to leave Iran and could be brought back
for trial again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
