<DOCNO> XIE19990410.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Complete Agrarian Reform Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- More than 90,000 hectares of land
have been turned over to Philippine farmers since the new
government took over on June 30 and almost 127,000 hectares more
are due for distribution soon in line with the goal of President
Joseph Estrada.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of the Philippine News Agency Saturday,
the Department of Agrarian Reform (DAR) has already distributed
90,779 hectares to farmers beneficiaries and another 126,699
hectares are in various stages of documentation prior to
distribution under the Comprehensive Agrarian Reform Program
(CARP) which the president plans to wrap up under his watch.
</P>
<P>
"Agrarian reform is one of the foundations of the Estrada
administration's commitment to food security, poverty reduction
and countryside development," DAR said in a performance report
submitted recently to the Presidential Palace.
</P>
<P>
The DAR reported that it has also executed 6,558 leasehold
contracts covering 13,450 hectares of land and benefiting 7,271
farmers and sponsored 1,202 training programs for 24,120
beneficiaries and field personnel.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, DAR vowed to complete the turnover of 1.3 million
hectares to farmers, representing the remaining 40 percent of
CARP-covered lands, in pursuit of President Estrada's 1998 order
for DAR to complete during his term the land reform program
implemented by the previous Aquino and Ramos administrations.
</P>
<P>
DAR Secretary Horacio Morales Jr. said the completion of CARP
is an integral part of the Estrada administration's three-pronged
comprehensive rural development policy.
</P>
<P>
The three components of this broad-based rural development
approach are food security and agricultural modernization,
equitable access to land and other natural resources and watershed
management and an ecosystems approach. 
</P>
</TEXT>
