<DOCNO> XIE19990410.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Official Confident of Basic Law Implementation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Elsie Leung, secretary for
Justice, said here Saturday that she has confidence in the full
implementation of the Basic Law with goodwill on both sides of the
mainland and Hong Kong and improved mutual understanding.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a symposium in commemoration of the ninth
anniversary of the promulgation of the Basic Law of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (SAR), Leung reviewed the
significant developments under the Basic Law in such important
areas as adaptation of laws and mutual legal assistance between
the SAR and the mainland.
</P>
<P>
Noting steady progress in the adaptation of laws, she said that
in the past year, a number of adaptation ordinances have been
passed. They deal with a wide range of matters, including
references to foreign countries, courts and tribunals,
interpretative provisions and nationality related matters.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-six other adaptation bills have been introduced and are
now going through the legislative process, she said.
</P>
<P>
Leung said important steps have been taken to develop mutual
legal assistance between the SAR and the mainland and progress in
this area has been encouraging.
</P>
<P>
In January this year, an agreement was signed in respect of the
mutual service of judicial documents in civil and commercial
proceedings between mainland and SAR courts.
</P>
<P>
This agreement provides the necessary rules to regulate the
service of judicial documents in civil and commercial proceedings
between the SAR and the rest of China and fills the vacuum created
when the relevant Hague Convention ceased to apply to cross-
boundary service after Hong Kong's return to China, she said.
</P>
<P>
In November last year, major principles were agreed with
relevant mainland authorities on the new arrangements for direct
and mutual recognition and enforcement of arbitral awards between
the SAR and the mainland.
</P>
<P>
Leung said a draft agreement is being discussed, with only a
small number of issues still outstanding.
</P>
<P>
She noted that the progress of the discussions between the SAR
government and the Central People's Government is encouraging and
it is hoped that agreement will be reached soon.
</P>
<P>
These positive developments are examples of close cooperation
between the mainland and the SAR.
</P>
<P>
"With such cooperation and the consolidated effort of the SAR
government and the people of Hong Kong, I trust that our
collective enterprise of translating the high principles and
values enshrined in the Basic Law into reality will be a huge
success," she said.
</P>
<P>
Leung said: "Although we have less than two years' experience
of operating under the Basic Law, its strengths are already
apparent."
</P>
<P>
She said the fact that controversial issues have arisen should
come as no surprise, adding, "I am confident that, with goodwill
on both sides and improved mutual understanding, the controversial
issues that must from time to time arise can all be satisfactorily
resolved within one country in accordance with the Basic Law."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
