<HEADLINE> FPDA to Conduct Exercise With Malaysia Re-joining </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The group of the Five Power
Defense Arrangement (FPDA) will conduct an air defense exercise
between April 14 and 21 with the participation of Malaysia which
decided to pull out of FPDA exercises last year.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore Ministry of Defense said in a news release
Saturday that air and naval forces from the FPDA, which groups
Australia, Malaysia, New Zealand, Singapore and Britain, will
participate in the 10-day exercise code-named Major ADEX 99-2.
</P>
<P>
Major ADEX 99-2 will be coordinated by the Headquarters
Integrated Air Defense System located at Royal Malaysian Air Force
Base Butterworth under the command of Air-Vice Marshal R.B.
Treloar and its aim is to exercise FPDA forces in protecting the
airspace of Peninsular Malaysia and Singapore and enhance
inter-operability, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The exercise will be the first joint FPDA action involving
Malaysia since the country decided in August 1998 to pull out of
FPDA exercises slated for last year because of the country's
economic woes and tense relations with Singapore at that time.
</P>
<P>
As a result of Malaysia's decision, a major maritime and air
exercise scheduled for the third quarter of last year by the FPDA
allies was unable to proceed.
</P>
<P>
The FPDA has existed for about 28 years and held joint
exercises almost every year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
