<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine National Railways Plans to Lure Private Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The state-owned Philippine
National Railways (PNR) is drafting a plan to lure private
investors, a report of the Philippine News Agency said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, PNR's plan is anchored on four pillars
-- the consolidation of PNR's control over the right-of-way and
real estate properties; concentration of development efforts on
the more lucrative commuter market; joint venture tie-ups with
private sector operators and retirement of PNR's outstanding
debts.
</P>
<P>
PNR chairman Carlos M. Borromeo was quoted as saying that PNR
is looking at joint venture arrangements with private operators to
provide a modern fleet of diesel electric trains, initially for
commuter or short haul services.
</P>
<P>
PNR also plans to earn more from the railways' 4,300 hectares
real estate assets which can generate at least 500 million pesos
(1 U.S. dollar is equal to about 40 pesos) in rental revenues.
</P>
<P>
PNR has 1,300 km railways, of which only 490 km are being used.
Its trains carry 700,000 passengers per year on its long distance
(Manila-Legaspi) route and at least four million passengers per
year on its short distance commuter trains.
</P>
<P>
However, less than 50 percent of the locomotives of PNR are
serviceable. As a result, the railway loses 75 pesos per long
distance passenger and 60 pesos per commuter, Borromeo said.
</P>
<P>
The national government subsidizes the railway at 10 million
pesos per month. PNR likewise relies on the national government to
service its 13 billion peso debt.
</P>
<P>
In terms of human resources, PNR has 2,300 employees, whom the
agency has neither the fleet nor the tracks to keep fully
employed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
