<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Cholera Cases Hit Kenyan Coast Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Over 30 new cases of cholera have
been disclosed following the onset of rains in Mombasa, a
southern coastal city, and other areas in Kenya's coast Province.
</P>
<P>
Provincial medical officer S.K. Shariff said the new reported
cases on the Mombasa Island and other areas had been admitted to
hospitals, while others admitted and discharged, the East African
Standard newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Shariff noted that there was no cholera-related death in the
province over the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
"New more cases are still coming up," he said, adding that
medical workers were alert and are taking all the measures to
control the situation.
</P>
<P>
The medical officer attributed the disease outbreak to the
re-opening of the food kiosks which do not maintain health
regulations. The kiosks had been closed due to the disease
outbreak barely a month ago.
</P>
<P>
In late March, the outbreak of cholera in this coast province
claimed 10 lives in a week.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper also reported that cholera also killed 15 people
in Banane division of Garissa District in North Eastern Province
in the past two days.
</P>
<P>
The epidemic was spread from neighboring Garbatula in Isiolo
District of Eastern Province, said the North Eastern Provincial
medical officer of health Mohammed Dahie. Dahie said that a
medical team left Friday evening to the affected area with
medical supplies and intravenous fluids in an emergency state to
curb the spread of the disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990410.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Get U.N. Food Donation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP) has
announced that it will supply Kenya with 85, 000 tons of food
worth 32.5 million U.S. dollars, in a bid to support the Kenyan
government in alleviating poverty.
</P>
<P>
The food aid will cover the period from now up to the year
2003, the Kenya Times newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"The program would cover school feeding, disaster preparedness
and community nutrition and care projects," said WFP regional
director Holdbrook Athur Friday, who is also in charge of the
agency's operations in the Horn of Africa.
</P>
<P>
Holdbrook said WFP assessment showed that small-scale farmers
living in the arid and semi-arid areas remain the most vulnerable
to food shortage.
</P>
<P>
"The poor cope with food shortage by reducing what the family
eat and withdrawing children, especially girls, from school,"
said the director.
</P>
<P>
He said it was common for children to have one meal a day in
Kenya's arid areas, adding that his organization viewed the
school feeding program as an effective way of ensuring school
attendance and improved academic performance.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the full school feeding program, Holdbrook said
the program, which started five years ago, will also cover the
provision of mid-morning snack of porridge and a hot lunch of
maize and beans to an average of 300,000 primary and pre-primary
school children.
</P>
<P>
He said more attention would be focused on arid and semi-arid
areas of the country and slums in cities.
</P>
<P>
On disasters, the director said the spiralling levels of
poverty and poor infrastructure, Kenyans were more vulnerable and
their ability to cope with disasters is decreasing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990410.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Relief Food Reaches Ethiopia's Drought Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian Disaster
Prevention and Preparedness Commission said the 5,000 tons of
relief food it sent for drought victims in eastern Somali region
has arrived in Jijiga, "the Ethiopian Herald" reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted a press release issued by the commission
as saying that the timely arrival would create favorable
conditions for distributing the relief food to the victims as soon
as possible.
</P>
<P>
The release said this is part of the 8,000 tons relief food
allocated for the year and the remaining 3,000 tons will shortly
be transported from the Nazareth warehouse.
</P>
<P>
According to the release, the 4,700 tons of relief food sent
earlier to the region has been distributed to the victims.
</P>
<P>
A lack of rainfall during the two previous rainy seasons in the
Somali region has not only exacerbated food shortage but also a
serious water shortage there. Relief agencies are making efforts
to fetch water to the drought stricken areas by tanker trucks.
</P>
<P>
A large number of livestock in Jijiga and Dagahabur districts
have died for lack of water, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The World Food Program has already reallocated 8,000 tons of
food aid to 640,000 drought stricken pastoralists in the region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
