<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 08:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Says It Kills 44 Kurdish Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- A total of 44 rebels of the
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) have been killed in a
cross-border offensive launched by Turkish troops, the
semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
It was the second reported cross-boder military operation
against the Kurdish rebels based in northern Iraq since PKK
leader Abdullah Ocalan was captured on February 15.
</P>
<P>
Some 15,000-strong Turkish troops, accompanied by 2,000
pro-government village guards, crossed into neighboring Iraq on
Tuesday to hunt down the Kurdish fighters.
</P>
<P>
The agency also reported that the Turkish troops had captured
15 PKK militants in the operation.
</P>
<P>
However, 10 soldiers of the Turkish government troops were also
killed in the conflict, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
During the offensive, Turkish warplanes bombarded PKK rebel
bases in the northeastern corner of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has frequently launched cross-border military operations
into northern Iraq in the spring after snow clears since Baghdad
was rendered ineffective in controlling the Kurdish-populated
region.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that guerrillas of the Iraq's Kurdistan
Democratic Party (KDP), which controls areas along the
Iraqi-Turkish border, has been supporting the Turkish troops in
fighting against the PKK militants.
</P>
<P>
The PKK led by Ocalan has been fighting a 15-year-old
guerrilla war for an independent Kurdish state in southeastern
Turkey since August 1984. Over 37,000 people, including PKK
rebels, government troops and civilians, have died in conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Ocalan has been jailed on Imrali Island in Marmara Sea near
Turkey's western province of Bursa on charges of treason. He may
face the death penalty if convicted.
</P>
<P>
A series of bombing attacks have been launched by Kurds in
protest of the capture of Ocalan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
