<HEADLINE> Chinese Bourses Step Up Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Managers of China's two
fledgling bourses, the Shanghai and Shenzhen Stock Exchanges, are
meeting in Shanghai this weekend to see if they can learn from
each other in fields like market supervision and internal
management, according to a source with the Shanghai bourse.
</P>
<P>
The Shenzhen Stock Exchange delegation, headed by the
Exchange's General Manager Gui Minjie, arrived in Shanghai Friday
and immediately paid a visit to the Shanghai bourse, said the
source.
</P>
<P>
"We share the common market, members and investors, and we
really can learn many things from each other in fields like
technology, management, liquidation and supervision," the source
quoted Gui as saying.
</P>
<P>
Gui also noted that the two bourses should further enhance
their cooperation to make greater contribution to China's economic
development, especially to the Chinese government's bid to help
loss-making state-owned enterprises out of their economic
difficulties within three years, the source added.
</P>
<P>
The two bourses Friday also held an exchange conference, the
first of its kind over the past eight years and more since the
founding of the bourses, said the source.
</P>
<P>
Tu Guangshao, general manager of the Shanghai Stock Exchange,
noted that such conference will become a regular form of exchange
between the two bourses in the future, according to the source.
</P>
<P>
There are now more than 800 listed companies on the Shanghai
and Shenzhen bourses, whose transaction volumes in 1998 reached 1.
24 trillion yuan and 1.1 trillion yuan respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
