<HEADLINE> Kenyan Shilling Holding Firm Against Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan shilling held steady
versus the U.S. dollar in trade Friday at the Nairobi Foreign
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
Five leading banks posted the shilling at 65.25/45 against the
dollar, unchanged from Thursday's close, a leading Kenyan
newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
However, the currency dealers here said that the local unit was
 vulnerable and likely to drift low on sustained dollar demand.
</P>
<P>
The shilling has come under pressure against the dollar in the
last two weeks, losing slightly more than one shilling, undermined
by a surge in demand for dollars not matched by inflows.
</P>
<P>
According to dealers, the energy and manufacturing sectors were
buying dollars to cover forward positions while offshore
investors were repatriating funds from the equity market.
</P>
<P>
"The importers have seen signs of shilling weakening further
and are now buying dollars although they don't have bills to
settle at the moment," one dealer said.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank of Kenya posted a shilling mean indicative
rate of 65. 29 shillings to the dollar compared to 65.00 shillings
at Thursday's open.
</P>
<P>
The shilling also opened softer against the pound and euro. The
bank posted a shilling mean indicative rate of 104.93 shillings
and 70.19 shillings respectively from 104.11 shillings and 70.10
shillings on Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
