<HEADLINE> Jordanian King Kicks off Visits to Oman, UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin
Hussein Saturday kicked off official visits to Oman and the
United Arab Emirates (UAE) in a bid to strengthen ties with the
two Gulf countries.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah is expected to meet with Oman's Sultan Qaboos Bin Said
during his 24-hour stay in Oman before he heads for UAE on Sunday
for talks with President Sheikh Zayed Al-Nahyan.
</P>
<P>
The visits were part of Abdullah's efforts to drum up support
from the Gulf countries for Jordan's stagnant economy, which
registered a negative economic growth in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah was expected to persuade leaders of the two countries
to further open up their markets to Jordanian labor. Jordan's
labor export constitute one of the three pillars of its economy
along with foreign aid and tourism.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Abdullah had paid a three-day visit to
Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
The monarch said upon his return from Riyadh that Jordan would
seek to further ties with the Arab states in the Gulf,
traditionally a stronghold for Jordanian labor.
</P>
<P>
His visits to the Gulf states were also aimed at amending
Jordan's ties with these countries, which were damaged during the
1990 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Jordan was isolated for its sympathy with Iraq's invasion of
Kuwait during the 1990-91 Gulf Crisis. 
</P>
