<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Multi-polarity Benefits World Peace, Stability: Li </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 10 (Xinhua) -- "The trend toward
multipolarization is in the interest of world peace and stability,
 and multipolarity is better than mono-polarity," visiting Chinese
leader Li Peng said here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"World affairs must not be dictated by one single country or a
handful of countries," said Li, chairman of the Standing Committee
of the National People's Congress (NPC) of China, in a speech
presided over by his Pakistani counterpart, Ellahi Bukhsh Soomro.
</P>
<P>
All countries, big or small, rich or poor, strong or weak, are
equal members in the big international family and all should be
respected, he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that another important mark of the development of
multipolarization is the continuous emergence of regional
organizations and groups.
</P>
<P>
Generally speaking, "this is a positive phenomenon in the
international political life," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Li said the present international situation in general
continued to move toward relaxation, but local elements of tension
and tumult are on the increase and new crises keep cropping up and
in some areas have even escalated to armed conflicts and wars.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese leader said, "the harsh facts have told us that
many contradictions covered in the past have been further
revealed and even intensified."
</P>
<P>
"The world is still not peaceful and tranquil," said Li.
</P>
<P>
Li noted that the world situation is undergoing profound
changes. Countries are now readjusting relations among
themselves, centering on a series of major issues such as
regional security, the economy and finance and sustainable
development.
</P>
<P>
In this context, he said, changes and impact ensuing from the
readjustment of relations among big countries have drawn extensive
 attention.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of economic globalization, Li said, "Economic
relations are an extremely important aspect of the current
international relations."
</P>
<P>
"International globalization is the inevitable result of the
worldwide flow and allocation of the essential factors of
production and hence the trend of the times," he noted.
</P>
<P>
On the whole, he said, this is conducive to international
interchange and economic development.
</P>
<P>
However, Li said, for the vast number of developing countries,
particularly those whose economic strength is still fairly
fragile, "economic globalization not only brings opportunities,
but also enormous risks and challenges."
</P>
<P>
He believed that the international community should work to
promote the establishment of "a peaceful, stable, just and
equitable new international political and economic order and a
new international financial system."
</P>
<P>
Li, who arrived here Thursday on a four-day official visit,
made the speech before a gathering of about 500 people including
members of the Pakistani National Assembly and Senate, senior
cabinet members and foreign diplomatic envoys in Pakistan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
