<HEADLINE> China Ready for Deeper Ties With S. Asia: Li Peng </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Li Peng, chairman of the
Standing Committee of the National People's Congress of China,
said here Saturday that China is ready to "write a new chapter of
friendly relations and cooperation" with South Asian nations.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a speech presided over by his Pakistani counterpart,
 Ellahi Bukhsh Soomro, Li said it serves the common interests of
both China and the South Asian nations to constantly expand and
increase bilateral cooperation and exchange.
</P>
<P>
As developing countries, China and the South Asian nations are
both faced with the common task of maintaining peace and promoting
development, Li said Li.
</P>
<P>
He said, "China will, as always, uphold the Five Principles of
Peaceful Coexistence and pursue the policy of good-neighborliness
and friendship."
</P>
<P>
Li appreciated the remarkable achievements made by the South
Asian nations in improving the quality of their people's life and
exploring a road of development suitable for their national
conditions.
</P>
<P>
Li noted that "the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC) played an increasingly active role in economic
 cooperation and political coordination in this region."
</P>
<P>
China, he said, sincerely hoped that the South Asian countries
would live in harmony and enjoy long-term stability and economic
development amidst the deepening trends of multipolarization and
economic globalization.
</P>
<P>
On the relations between the two South Asian neighbors of
Pakistan and India, Li said China is pleased to note the
important agreements reached recently by the prime ministers of
the two countries in a bid to improve the bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The two countries, through friendly talks, issued the Lahore
Declaration and other important instruments in February this year
and jointly declared that they would accelerate their efforts to
settle all issues between them, including the Kashmir issue, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
"There is no doubt that this positive development is in the
interest of peace and stability in this region," said the Chinese
leader.
</P>
<P>
He also said it is China's consistent position "to solve issues
left over from history by means of peaceful negotiation and iron
out differences among countries through friendly consultation."
</P>
<P>
China highly appraises the important agreements reached by the
leaders of Pakistan and India in a bid to improve the bilateral
relations, Li said, adding that they accord with the long-term and
fundamental interests of the two countries and the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
Li said he is confident that the peoples in the South Asian
region would tap their huge potential and build an even better
future.
</P>
<P>
Li, who arrived here Thursday on a four-day official visit to
this South Asian nation at the invitation of Soomro, made the
speech before a gathering of about 500 people including members of
the Pakistani National Assembly and Senate, cabinet members and
foreign diplomatic envoys in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan is the fourth leg of Li's current six-nation tour. He
has already visited Greece, Turkey and Syria. After his visit to
Pakistan, Li will proceed to Bangladesh and Thailand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
