<HEADLINE> Access to Global Markets: Kenyan President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Past experiences have shown that
 developing countries can attain economic prosperity not only
through reforms but greater access to international market,
Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Moi made the remarks when he officially opened a meeting of the
Economic Committee of the Global Coalition for Africa in Nairobi,
the Kenya Times paper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He noted that reforms had led to substantial reduction in
public expenditure in some important sectors, leaving the private
sector to play an increasingly greater role in the development of
those sectors.
</P>
<P>
The president pointed out that the changes which a number of
African countries were undertaking were a result of rapid changes
taking place in the international trading system, which forced
them to implement social and economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
Moi told the participants from the continent that agriculture
played a vital role in the economic development of Africa.
</P>
<P>
"Agriculture not only plays a role of feeding our fast growing
 populating, but also takes a greater role in absorbing a large
population as well as generating incomes which is crucial in
eradicating poverty," he said.
</P>
<P>
"In addition it provides the bulk of our exports and supplies
raw materials to our industries," the president added.
</P>
<P>
He urged participants to discuss in detail issues affecting
the agro- sector and how to improve productivity, citing weather
as a major cause of low productivity that called for planned
farming activities to fit changing weather patterns. 
</P>
