<DOCNO> XIE19990410.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Six Dead In U.S. Midwest Storms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 9 (Xinhua) -- At least six people died and
dozens were injured on Friday in a spring storm that spawned
dozens of tornadoes in the midwest states.
</P>
<P>
Two persons were killed in Illinois as powerful storms tore
through the Midwest overnight; another two were killed in a house,
and the rest two in separate car crashes. Three local hospitals
said they had treated 32 people for injuries.
</P>
<P>
The worst hit area appeared to be the affluent Ohio village of
Montgomery, about 32 kilometers northeast of downtown Cincinnati,
where about 200 homes were demolished and 400 damaged. Ohio's
Emergency Management Agency said about 200,000 customers lost
power.
</P>
<P>
The National Weather Service said it had received reports of 64
tornadoes in Iowa, Missouri, Nebraska and Illinois on Thursday and
Friday, most of them in rural areas where no damage resulted.
</P>
<P>
It had issued a warning as the storm system sped out of the
Great Plains, saying it posed a very high risk of severe weather
in the Mississippi Valley.
</P>
<P>
Ohio's Governor Bob Taft declared three counties emergency
areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
