<DOCNO> XIE19990410.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, April 10 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov and U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will meet in Oslo, the
capital of Norway, next Tuesday to discuss the crisis in Kosovo,
the Russian Foreign Ministry said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is aimed at jointly seeking a political solution to
the Kosovo crisis. The two officials are also expected to discuss
current relations between Russia and the United States, the ITAR-
Tass news agency reported. This is the first formal meeting
between Ivanov and Albright since NATO launched air strikes
against Yugoslavia on March 24. (Russia-US-Yugoslavia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- The Italian government voiced support on Friday for an
appeal by United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan urging
Yugoslavia to halt military action in Kosovo and withdraw its army
and militia forces from the province.
</P>
<P>
In a long telephone conversation with Annan, Italian Prime
Minister Massimo D'Alema said he and his government are firmly
behind the appeal and hope Annan's words would be heeded and win
the support of the entire U.N. Security Council. Annan called on
Belgrade to end its "campaign of intimidation and deportation" of
civilians, and allow the return of refugees and the deployment of
an international military force to ensure the safety of these
people and the arrival of humanitarian aid shipments. (Italy-UN-
Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- Albania will recognize the "Kosovo government"
established by the Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA) early this month,
said Albanian Prime Minister Pandeli Majko on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The self-claimed government, which consists of members of the
KLA and the Kosovo Democratic United Front seeking separation of
the province from the Republic of Serbia, Yugoslavia, has not won
any international recognition. During an interview with local TV,
Majko voiced support to the self-claimed government headed by
Hasim Thaci. (Albania-Accord)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ZAGREB -- Croatian Prime Minister Zlatko Matesa said his
country is "unable to receive more ethnic Albanian refugees from
Kosovo," when he met with the UN High Commissioner for Refugees (
UNHCR) mission leader in Croatia Robert Robinson here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Due to a "limited capacity," Croatia can only receive a small
number of refugees in addition to some 5,000 Kosovar refugees
already in the country, Matesa said. Noting that Croatia also has
some 100,000 refugees from Bosnia in its territory, he said the
UNHCR does understand Croatia's predicament. (Croatia-Yugoslavia-
Refugees) 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
