<DOCNO> XIE19990410.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Djibouti Ruling Party Wins Presidential Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ismail Omar won Friday's poll with 74.1 percent of the vote and
will become Djibouti's second president since independence,
Interior Minister Elmi Obseih wais said on state television, a
report from the Djibouti capital said.
</P>
<P>
Opposition-backed candidate Moussa Ahmed Idriss gained 25.9
percent on a 60.4 percent turnout of 103,500 voters.
</P>
<P>
Djibouti is a city-state of just 600,000 at the southern end
of the Red Sea, seen as an oasis of stability next to strife-torn
Ethiopia, Eritrea and Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Ismail Omar, 52, will take over from Hassan Gouled Aptidon,
83, who joined a rare breed of regional leaders in February by
announcing he would step down voluntarily from power after 22
years.
</P>
<P>
The new leader worked for two decades as cabinet director in
Hassan Gouled's office and was also the head of the security
services.
</P>
<P>
Elmi Obseih stressed the validity of the poll and denied
opposition charges of fraud.
</P>
<P>
The port and trade with Ethiopia are vital to Djibouti's economy
as are links to France, which has around 3,000 troops stationed in
the Horn of Africa country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
