<HEADLINE> Belgrade Passes Through Calm Night Since NATO Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Friday night was the most
peaceful in Belgrade since NATO started its attacks against
Yugoslavia on March 23, although the air strike alarm remained in
force until early Saturday, the Tanjug news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the country's warning center, the huge sounds
heard overnight were made by the Yugoslav air defense force in
counterattacking NATO planes.
</P>
<P>
On Friday night, NATO planes destroyed the TV tower in the
suburbs of Pristina, the capital of Kosovo, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, thousands of citizens from Belgrade, Novi Sad and
Leskovac had for the fifth night gotten together on the bridges
across the Sava River and the Danube River to protect them with
their bodies from being bombed by NATO planes.
</P>
<P>
As NATO has also threatened to bomb the Serb radio and TV
stations, hundreds of journalists stayed around the station
building on Friday night to protect it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
