<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Seminar Marks Basic Law Promulgation Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 10 (Xinhua) -- More than 300 people from all
walks of life in Hong Kong attended a symposium here Saturday in
commemoration of the ninth anniversary of the promulgation of the
Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR).
</P>
<P>
In her welcoming remarks at the symposium on "Knowing One
Country, Realizing Two Systems", Ko Siu Wah, convenor of the Joint
Committee for the Promotion of the Basic Law, noted that since
Hong Kong's return to China, the Central Government has been firm
in observing the principles of "one country, two systems" and "
Hong Kong people running Hong Kong" with a high degree of autonomy.
</P>
<P>
While refraining from intervening into the internal affairs of
the SAR, the Central Government has been supportive to the SAR
government in running its own affairs.
</P>
<P>
The SAR government has, on the other hand, enacted legislation
on its own according to the Basic Law, exercised independent
judicial power, handled its internal affairs without any
intervention, and made important decisions on matters pertinent to
the economy and well-being of its people.
</P>
<P>
She said the People's Liberation Army garrison has stringently
abide by the Basic Law and Garrison Law, and refrained from
intervening into the internal affairs of the SAR.
</P>
<P>
Looking ahead, She said, the SAR will have to face challenges
of all kinds. In order for Hong Kong to function properly and to
maintain stability and prosperity, it is crucial that the people
of Hong Kong get to know, and thoroughly understand, the Basic Law,
she added.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Yam, chief executive of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority,
dwelt on the implementation of financial policies in the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the experience of the SAR government since its
establishment shows not only that Hong Kong enjoys an even higher
degree of monetary autonomy after the transfer of power, but also
that its monetary relationship with the mainland has been handled
strictly in accordance with the "one country, two systems"
principle.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the belief that the "one country, two systems"
principle will continue to play an important role in the 21st
century, and that both the mainland and Hong Kong will stand to
reap immense benefits from it.
</P>
<P>
Other speakers at the symposium also included Kwan Wing-shing,
senior economic research manager of the Hang Seng Bank, Tsang Shu-
ki, professor of Economics Hong Kong Baptist University, and Wang
Ying Wai, chairman of the Business and Professionals' Federation
of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The symposium was sponsored by the Joint Committee for the
Promotion of the Basic Law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
