<HEADLINE> Lebanese Group Stages Campaign to Aid Kosovars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 10 (Xinhua) -- A public campaign to aid Kosovo's
refugees has been staged in Lebanon and will continue until the
end of the month, the Daily Star reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The campaign was launched by al-Jamaa al-Islimiya, a Islamist
group in the country's southern largest port city of Sidon.
</P>
<P>
Imams who led Friday prayers urged worshippers to contribute
to the group's campaign and voiced concerns that the 800,000
Kosovar refugees displaced in recent weeks might face the same
fate as the Palestinians did more than 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Ibrahim Masri, director-general of the group, told the paper
that the group had placed newspaper ads calling on the public to
aid the refugees.
</P>
<P>
"The money will be transferred to the refugees through
philanthropic associations based in Europe," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Contributions have been made before the campaign was
officially launched. Last week, al-Jamaa collected more than 30
million Lebanese pounds (about 20,000 U.S. dollars) from
worshippers in Beirut Mosques," he added.
</P>
<P>
With NATO intensifies its air strikes on Yugoslavia, thousands
of residents in the ethnic Albanian-predominated Kosovo are
fleeing to neighboring countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
