<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Djibouti Ruling Party Leads in Presidential Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NAIROBI, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Djibouti's ruling alliance took
a clear early lead Saturday as results streamed in from an
election for the presidency of the small Red Sea state, Interior
Minister Elmi Obsieh Wais announced.
</P>
<P>
With around half of results counted after Friday's poll,
Ismail Omar Guelleh, the candidate of the ruling alliance party,
had around 60 percent of the vote, according to reports from the
country's capital Djibouti.
</P>
<P>
Ismail Omar is running against opposition-backed candidate
Moussa Ahmed Idriss to become only the second president of
Djibouti since its independence from France in 1977.
</P>
<P>
The winner will take over from Hassan Gouled Aptidon, 83, who
joined a rare breed of regional leaders in February when he
announced he would step down from power voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
A stream of sealed glass ballot boxes arrived under escort at
city hall late friday and officials worked through the night to
collate results by the light of electric generators, while outside
armed police stood guard in the desert heat.
</P>
<P>
With just 600,000 people, Djibouti is a country whose majority
 population live in the dry and dusty capital which sprawls along
the coast from a port at the southern end of the Red Sea.
</P>
<P>
The port and trade with Ethiopia are vital and for years
Djibouti has been an oasis of stability next to Ethiopia, Eritrea
and Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Economic support from France, which has around 3,000 troops
stationed in the country, is also critical, observers in the Horn
of Africa country said.
</P>
<P>
A western diplomat predicted Friday that the election would
likely yield an easy victory for Ismail Omar, who headed the
security services and has years of experience in government.
</P>
</TEXT>
