<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand's Trade Balance Deteriorates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The trend in New Zealand's
merchandise trade balance has deteriorated in recent months, New
Zealand Government Statistician Len Cook said here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In a media release, Cook explained that this deterioration is
because New Zealand's imports trend has continued to rise while
the exports trend has flattened.
</P>
<P>
"Low world commodity prices and the recent appreciation of the
New Zealand dollar appear to be hampering export growth" of New
Zealand, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the media release, for the month of February the
provisional merchandise trade balance of New Zealand was in
surplus by 9 million NZ dollars (4.82 million U.S. dollars), with
its exports standing at 1.807 billion NZ dollars (975.8 million
U.S. dollars). Over the last 10 years trade surpluses over 100
million NZ dollars (54 million U.S. dollars) have been typical
for the month of February.
</P>
<P>
"World commodity prices remain low for products such as wool
and meat. Economic difficulties in Russia have reduced demand for
butter and cheese but total dairy exports are still high. Exports
of seafood and electrical goods continued to show strong growth.
Exports of wood and wood products have shown some signs of
recovery recently," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
In recent months, he said, there has been some recovery in
demand from Asia and this is reflected in increased exports to the
Republic of Korea and the People's Republic of China. However, he
added, imports from Asia have continued to grow strongly. "This
has resulted in the fifth monthly merchandise trade deficit with
Asia in the last seven months. Before this, there had only been
two months in deficit since 1990," Cook said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990410.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Government on Course for Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand government
remains on course to book a small operating budget surplus in the
year from July 1998 to June 1999.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand Treasury figures for the eight months to February,
which were made public here Saturday, show an operating budget
surplus of 1.1 billion NZ dollars (594 million U.S. dollars) in
the
period, 79 million NZ dollars (42.6 million U.S. dollars) ahead of

forecast.
</P>
<P>
Local economists expect a surplus of a few hundred million NZ
dollars in the year to June 1999. This excludes the sale of state-
owned Contact Energy which is going ahead and local economists
estimate this will swell the budget surplus for the year to
between
1.5 billion and 2 billion NZ dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to the figures, in the eight months to February the
government revenue totaled 23.28 billion NZ dollars (12.57 billion

U.S. dollars) and its expenses 22.93 billion NZ dollars (12.38
billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
At present, the net debt of the New Zealand government is 24.42

billion NZ dollars (13.19 billion U.S. dollars), 24.9 percent of
the
country's GDP, down 743 million NZ dollars (401 million U.S.
dollars)
on forecast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
