<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: ABCs of Macao SAR Basic Law (22) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Following is Part 22 of a
question and answer series of the ABCs of the Basic Law of the
Macao Special Administrative Region (MSAR).
</P>
<P>
Over what acts shall the courts of the MSAR have no
jurisdiction?
</P>
<P>
According to Article 19 of the Basic Law, the courts of the
Macao Special Administrative Region shall have no jurisdiction
over acts of State such as national defense and foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
State acts include decisions made or steps taken by the highest
organ of State power and the highest organ of State administration
in exercising State sovereignty, such as declaring war, making
peace, recognizing foreign government, dispatching diplomatic
envoys to foreign countries, signing treaties with foreign
countries, issuing order of official appointment and removal and
proclaiming martial law, etc.
</P>
<P>
State acts give expression to State sovereignty and represent
national interests. Therefore, while the courts of the MSAR enjoy
independent judicial power and power of final adjudication, they
have no jurisdiction over the above State acts.
</P>
<P>
Since the courts of the MSAR may not know in advance whether
cases they try involve State acts, it is stipulated in Article 19
of the Basic Law that the courts of the Region shall obtain a
certificate from the Chief Executive on questions of fact
concerning acts of State such as national defense and foreign
affairs whenever such questions arise in trying cases. This
certificate shall be binding on the courts.
</P>
<P>
Before issuing such a certificate, the Chief Executive shall
obtain a certifying document from the Central People's Government.
For example, if a person who faces criminal prosecution in the
MSAR claims he is an accredited foreign diplomat in China, it
involves the question of act of State in diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
The court should obtain a certificate from the Chief Executive
on his status. If it is ascertained that he is an accredited
foreign diplomat in China, the court then has no jurisdiction over
this case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
