<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shaanxi to Step Up Environmental Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Shaanxi Province
will intensify its efforts to combat pollution and improve the
quality of the local environment, a senior local official said
here today.
</P>
<P>
"We'll spare no effort to make the sky over our heads become
bluer," said Cheng Andong, governor of Shaanxi, in an interview
with journalists from Beijing.
</P>
<P>
In the next few years, Cheng said, Shaanxi will mainly focus on
fighting air pollution, and thus will actively promote the use of
natural gas.
</P>
<P>
In order to encourage more automobiles to adopt natural gas as
their fuel, the local government has lowered the price of natural
gas for car use and built a number of natural gas filling stations,
said the governor.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, natural gas pipes will extend into over 70 percent
of urban households in Shaanxi by the end of this year, and an
American company, the Jiuwun International Resources Inc., has
decided to invest 400 million US dollars to develop a clean fuel
project in Xi'an, capital of Shaanxi.
</P>
<P>
For the area in the northern part of Shaanxi, however, the main
environmental problem is desertification and soil erosion, Cheng
noted.
</P>
<P>
Located on the Loess Plateau in north China, the area is
reputed as "the cradle of the Chinese revolution", as its regional
center Yan'an served as the headquarters of the Chinese communists
for more than a decade in the 1930s and 40s.
</P>
<P>
"Local governments in the area are planting trees along the
sides of all major highways and roads in the areas, and the forest
and grassland coverage in the regions of Yan'an and Yulin has now
exceeded 40 percent," said Cheng.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that at present there have been 67 environment
monitoring stations across Shaanxi, while 104 smog and dust
control zones have been set up in 13 cities in the province.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
