<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Plant 100m Trees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has started a
nationwide afforestation campaign in which 100 million trees will
be planted by next year, government officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
President Benjamin Mkapa launched the campaign Saturday in the
Mwanza Region on the shore of Lake Victoria, while Vice-President
Omar Ali Juma and Prime Minister Frederick Sumaye are expected to
plant trees in Iringa and Rukwa regions in the southwest
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet ministers and regional commissioners are joining the
drive in other regions to avert possible desertification in the
east African country.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania is facing a series of environmental problems like
desertification, loss of wildlife habitat and deterioration of
aquatic ecosystems, the Minister of State, Edward Lowassa, said at
a session of the United Nations Environmental Governing Council in
Nairobi, Kenya last February.
</P>
<P>
Desertification is threatening 61 percent of Tanzania's arable
land, putting at risk the livelihood of 17 million people out of
30 million.
</P>
<P>
Most bare lands in Tanzania today were covered with thick
evergreen forests between 1950s and 1960s.
</P>
<P>
Increasing population pressure, felling of wood for charcoal,
fires, and development of industries like tobacco have made the
country lose 300,000 to 400,000 hectares of forests a year, while
less than 200,000 hectares of forests are planted annually,
environmentalists said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
