<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Natural Vitamin E Twice as Effective as Synthetic Version: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 9 (Xinhua) -- New health studies show that
natural vitamin E -- made of vegetable oils from soybeans, corn
and sunflowers -- is twice as effective in health benefits than
the synthetic chemically-manufactured version, a U.S. research
information service reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
There have also been indications that higher dosages of vitamin
E are safe and healthy, said a research summary issued by Veris, a
non-profit corporation which provides information on the role of
nutrition in health.
</P>
<P>
Vitamin E has been found to work effectively as a major
antioxidant and fight off free radicals in the body. Free radicals
have been shown to contribute to the development of a number of
diseases such as heart ailments, cancer and Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
The Veris research summary noted that while there has been a
general scientific assumption that natural and synthetic vitamins
are equal because of similar molecular structure, "vitamin E is
the exception."
</P>
<P>
"The bioavailability of natural sources of vitamin E is greater
than that of synthetic forms," based on both human and animal
studies, the research summary concluded.
</P>
<P>
These studies have shown an obvious difference between natural
and synthetic vitamin E, and this difference is more noticeable
after absorption in the digestive tract, while natural vitamin E
is retained significantly longer in body tissue.
</P>
<P>
Previously accepted differences between natural and synthetic
versions were "underestimated," the research summary noted, and
said that the bioavailability of natural vitamin E is
approximately twice that of synthetic compounds.
</P>
<P>
Two separate reports on natural vitamin E were particularly
cited in Veris research. One is from East Tennessee State
University and the other from Oregon State University. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
