<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major U.S. Airlines Hike Domestic Fares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Three major U.S. airlines have
raised leisure fares 3 percent and walkup fares 1 percent as of
Friday, a move that marked the third rate increase this year.
</P>
<P>
Continental Airlines, No.5 in the country, was the first to
increase fares, followed quickly by Delta Airlines and United
Airlines.
</P>
<P>
But Northwest Airlines Corp. said it had not raised its fares
while a spokesman for American Airlines said he did not know
whether the airline will match the increase.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, Northwest failed to go along with four of
the six increases by rivals. Other airlines quickly dropped back,
cutting their fares to stay competitive.
</P>
<P>
The two fare hikes that did succeed this year have already
raised leisure fares by 7 percent and business fares 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
If this one sticks, that will mean a 10 percent air fare
increase in the first three months of the year.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attribute the fare increases to a thriving economy
that has boosted demand to record levels for many carriers.
Besides, a recent rebound from last year's plunge in fuel prices
has made it more expensive for airlines to fly their planes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
