<HEADLINE> Singapore Growth May Exceed Official Forecast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
SINGAPORE, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's economy can grow by
more than one percent this year, surpassing earlier official
forecast of minus one to plus one percent, said Deputy Prime
Minister Tony Tan Friday.
</P>
<P>
Tan made the upbeat assessment of Singapore's economic situation
in the first quarter of this year in his keynote address to the
annual meeting of the Asia-Pacific Council of the American Chamber
of Commerce in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
"If there are no serious disturbances in the region and the U.S.
economic growth remains strong, growth for 1999 could well be
higher than the minus one percent to one percent range forecast by
the Ministry of Trade and Industry in February this year." Tan
noted.
</P>
<P>
He said that industrial production rose 6.1 percent in January
and February this year and leading economic indicators such as the
Composite Leading Index which leads the economy by about nine
months, continued their upward trend.
</P>
<P>
Leading Singapore businessmen have expressed optimism on the
near-term economic growth and economists also expect a faster pace
than the official suggestion.
</P>
<P>
Singapore's economy fell into recession from the second half of
1998, shrinking by 0.6 percent in the third quarter and a further
0.8 percent in the fourth quarter as a result of the regional
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Tan said that in the first quarter of this year, however, the
economy has seen some tentative signs of recovery in response to
the upturn in the global electronics cycle.
</P>
<P>
The Asian economies are beginning to bottom out of their
economic difficulties, said Tan, adding that Singapore has earned
from the crisis a sense of urgency to restructure its economy and
reassess its capabilities and growth strategies.
</P>
<P>
He also promised a continued Singapore effort to offer
attractive opportunities to investors as he warned that an Asian
recovery will depend on the accessibility of the U.S. market by
Asian economies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
