<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Croatia Unable to Receive More Kosovar Refugees: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Croatian Prime Minister Zlatko
Matesa said his country is "unable to receive more ethnic Albanian
refugees from Kosovo," when he met with the UN High Commissioner
for Refugees (UNHCR) mission leader in Croatia Robert Robinson
here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Due to a "limited capacity," Croatia can only receive a small
number of refugees in addition to some 5,000 Kosovar refugees
already in the country, Matesa said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Croatia also has some 100,000 refugees from Bosnia
in its territory, he said the UNHCR does understand Croatia's
predicament.
</P>
<P>
Matesa stressed that Croatia has always received and settled
refugees and is willing to do all it can to provide the necessary
logistical assistance.
</P>
<P>
He said the Croatian government has decided to earmark 2.4
million U.S. dollars to help Kosovar refugees. The first shipment
of medical aid from Croatia, worth more than 400,000 dollars,
arrived in Albania on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Reports say that NATO's air strikes against Yugoslavia have so
far caused a loss of at least one billion dollars to Croatia's
economy, notably in its tourism and foreign trade sector because
of its proximity to the war zone.
</P>
<P>
Croatia, an active supporter of NATO, has come to bear the
brunt of NATO's military operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
