<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhu Urges U.S. Organizations' Support for China's WTO Entry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese Premier Zhu
Rongji Friday called on U.S. organizations and enterprises to
support China's efforts to join the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
"China has made many concessions within its capability for the
entry into the WTO as a developing country," Zhu said in his
speech delivered at a dinner hosted in his honor by seven U.S.
organizations including the America-China Society, the Asia
Society and the U.S.-China Policy Foundation.
</P>
<P>
He said China's joining the WTO will not only benefit the world
trade, but also conduce to the China-U.S. trade.
</P>
<P>
It has been 13 years since the negotiations started on China's
resumption of the General Agreement on Trade and Tariff (GATT)
membership and later its access to the WTO.
</P>
<P>
China's concessions for its bid to joining the WTO are big
enough as a developing country, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese premier expressed his appreciation of U.S.
organizations and enterprises for their efforts to ask the U.S.
Congress to approve an agreement on China's joining the WTO.
</P>
<P>
Zhu arrived in the United States on Tuesday for an eight-day
official visit to the country, the first by a Chinese premier in
15 years.
</P>
<P>
On the deficit the United States registered in its trade with
China, Zhu said that the issue could be resolved only through
joint efforts by the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"If the United States lifts the restrictions on its high-tech
export to China, I think the U.S. trade deficit will be narrowed,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
