<DOCNO> XIE19990410.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Joint Efforts Needed for Sino-U.S. Trade Balance: Zhu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 9 (Xinhua) -- China and the United States
should make joint efforts to improve the balance of trade between
the two countries, visiting Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji said here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhu made the remarks at a dinner hosted in his honor by
seven organizations including America-China Society, Asia Society
and the U.S.-China Policy Foundation.
</P>
<P>
"If we are to narrow the trade imbalance and expand the trade
volume, it requires efforts by both sides," he said.
</P>
<P>
The United States has become China's second largest trade
partner while China the fourth largest trade partner of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few years, trade imbalance has become a sticking
point in Sino-U.S. trade relations.
</P>
<P>
China's 1998 trade surplus with the United States was about 21
billion U.S. dollars while the United States put the figure as
high as 57 billion dollars due to different calculation methods.
</P>
<P>
Zhu, who is currently paying an eight-day official visit to the
United states, urged the United States to lift its restrictions on
export to China. He said the United States only sells wheat and
citrus to China rather than computers and satellites.
</P>
<P>
"If we are able to work together in areas like energy,
environment protection and telecommunications and have good
cooperation, in a few years from now, the trade deficit may be
China's rather than America's," he said.
</P>
<P>
"But if the United States wants to impose restrictions in many
areas, it might be very hard to achieve a balance of trade, so let
us work together," he added.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. support for China's entry into the Word Trade
Organization (WTO) is not only good for the global trade but also
good for the trade balance between China and the United States, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese premier pointed out that there are broad prospects
for cooperation on energy and environment protection between the
two countries, which will also help improve the trade balance.
</P>
<P>
"China's needs and the size of its markets in this sector can
be measured by billions of dollars," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Today we are talking about the trade deficit the U.S. has with
China, but perhaps a few years from now we will be talking about
China's trade deficit," he said.
</P>
<P>
This year witnesses the 20th anniversary of the establishment
of Sino-U.S. diplomatic relations and the signing of the Sino-U.S.
Trade Agreement.
</P>
<P>
China's General Customs Administration figures show a bilateral
trade volume approaching 55 billion dollars in 1998, more than 22
times the figure for 1979. From 1979 to 1998, bilateral trade was
worth 364.5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
U.S. figures show bilateral trade volume growing 35 times over
the past 20 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990410.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Digs China's First Cross-River Pedestrian Tunnel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 10 (Xinhua) -- China's largest city Shanghai
has dug the country's first cross-river pedestrian tunnel under
the Huangpu River, which flows through Shanghai and divides the
city in two.
</P>
<P>
Excavation of the 646.7-meter tunnel, which links the Bund area
on the west side of the Huangpu River to the Oriental Pearl TV
tower in Pudong, or regions east of the river, was concluded today.
The tunnel is expected to be completed on October 1 and put in use
at the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Constructors said that the tunnel, with a total investment of
500 million yuan (about 60 million US dollars), has an internal
diameter of 7 meters and will be beautifully decorated.
</P>
<P>
Once completed, the tunnel can transport some 5,000 people
every hour, and it will take a pedestrian only 2.5 to 5 minutes to
cross the river by taking a special fully-automated pedestrian
carrier, they added.
</P>
<P>
Areas west of the Huangpu River constitute Shanghai's old city
proper, including the country's most famous commercial districts
like the Nanjing Road and the Huaihai Road, while Pudong is a
booming new development area with the ambition of becoming China's
financial center.
</P>
<P>
Cross-river transportation in Shanghai currently depends on
ferry steamers, cable-suspended bridges and tunnels for auto
vehicles only. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
