<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai, U.S. Troops to Hold Joint Exercise Next Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Thailand and the United States
will begin a joint military exercise in Thailand next month,
according to Thai army Chief-of-Staff Gen. Chokechai Hongthong.
</P>
<P>
The annual "Cobra Gold" joint Thai-U.S. military exercise, one
of the largest involving U.S. forces in the Asia-Pacific this
year, will be held from May 12-25.
</P>
<P>
About 12,000 troops from the number of U.S. bases around the
Pacific including Alaska, Hawaii, Guam, Japan and south Korea,
will join their Thai counterparts, Chokechai was quoted Saturday
by the Bangkok Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
The exercise will involve air, sea and land operations in
Thailand's northeastern region and the Gulf of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Cobra Gold was started in 1982. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
