<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Cuts Key Rates Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Central Bank has
announced it will further cut its key rates as part of efforts to
bring down interest rates and spur borrowing by corporations and
industries.
</P>
<P>
Manila Standard newspaper Saturday quoted the Central Bank
Governor Gabriel Singson as saying that the forthcoming rate cut
will take effect on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The ninth cut this year will bring the Central Bank's overnight
borrowing rates to 11.375 percent, and lending rates to 13.375
percent from the old rates of 11.75 percent and 13.75 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Singson noted the move would bring the cumulative decline in
the overnight rates to two percentage points since the start of
the year.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank also decided to slash the reserve requirement
against bank deposits by one percentage point to free an
additional 11 billion peso (1 U.S. dollar is equal to about 40
pesos) funds into the financial system. The bank also agreed to
exempt new loans from the mandatory two-percent provisioning for
probable loan losses.
</P>
<P>
"The monetary authorities have taken these steps in an
environment of falling inflation and continued stability of the
peso exchange rate, " Singson said.
</P>
<P>
The reduction in overnight rates would send a signal to banks
to lend their money to the private sector rather than to the
Central Bank given the much lower rate offered by the Central
Bank.
</P>
<P>
The recent move is also expected to influence the yields on the
auction for Treasury bills on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Both Singson and Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu Believed
the bellwether 91-day Treasury bill rate could go below 11 percent
this month with combined efforts by the monetary and fiscal
sectors to bring down interest rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
