<DOCNO> XIE19990410.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Senate Approves Alien Business Bill in Principle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's senate has approved in
principle an alien business bill which will allow foreigners to
open a variety of new businesses and even hold a majority
shareholding in a company, a TV report said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Senators late on Friday voted 76:1 for the Alien Business Bill
forwarded by the lower house on Wednesday. A 35-member panel was
set up to scrutinize it.
</P>
<P>
Senator Sen Burapa Attakorn, in response to objection to the
bill for "opening up the country unlimitedly" to foreigners, said
free enterprises by aliens would lead to competition which would
ultimately benefit Thais more than the aliens themselves.
</P>
<P>
He said a number of countries had prospered primarily because
they had opened themselves up for broader foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
The bill allows foreigners to engage in the following fields:
</P>
<P>
-- Construction of infrastructure which relies on "special"
technology and expertise if a foreigner can provide a minimum of
500 million baht (13.5 million U.S. dollars) in operating funds;
</P>
<P>
-- Brokerage in the stock market or farm futures market;
</P>
<P>
-- Accounting, legal and engineering services;
</P>
<P>
-- Milling rice and making flour from rice or other crops, and
</P>
<P>
-- Import or export businesses, with a minimum operating fund
of 100 million baht (2.7 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
But the bill bans foreigners from a number of businesses for
"special reasons". These businesses include:
</P>
<P>
-- Publishing newspapers and broadcasting radio or television
programs;
</P>
<P>
-- Farming, raising livestock and fruit growing;
</P>
<P>
-- Logging and making products from timber;
</P>
<P>
-- Sales of Thai artifacts and other historical objects, and
</P>
<P>
-- Fishing in Thai territorial waters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
