<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Foils Tamil Rebel Attack on Colombo Port </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan Navy has busted a
Tamil rebel plan to launch a simultaneous land and sea borne
attack on the Colombo port, the official Daily News reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
A group of 14 rebels, belong to both their Black Tiger and Sea
Tiger Units were to have participated in this attack scheduled on
February 14, said the report, quoting naval intelligence sources.
</P>
<P>
The report said police arrested the suspected group leader
Adaikalam Anthony Amaradas, alias Aiyamanni Mohana, late last
month and had begun interrogating him.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the suspect had been decorated by the rebel
leader Prabhakaran himself for coming first among 35 competitors
in a five mile sea swim organized by the rebels.
</P>
<P>
The planned attack on the Colombo port was busted when the navy
arrested a suspected Black Tiger cadre in Colombo a few months
ago.
</P>
<P>
Navy sources believe that the other members of the group are
still in the northern Wanni area controlled by the Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) rebels.
</P>
<P>
"The LTTE does not send their cadres en masse to Colombo, but
instead, they are sent one by one," the report quoted navy sources
as saying.
</P>
<P>
They said the rehearsals on the planned attack had even taken
place in the Wanni area under the supervision of Black Tiger
trainers.
</P>
<P>
Investigations are continuing to detect the cache of armaments
and explosives required for this attack.
</P>
<P>
LTTE rebels have been fighting the Sri Lankan government since
1983 for a separate homeland in the north and east of the country.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
