<HEADLINE> Asia Wealth Bank Opens 25th Branch in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The Asia Wealth Bank (AWB), one of
the leading private banks in Myanmar, opened a branch on Friday in
Sittway, Rakhine state, bringing the total number of its branches
to 25 across the country, official newspaper The New Light of
Myanmar reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The AWB, first established with a capital of 60 million Kyats
(200,000 U.S. dollars) and 84 staff, had grown to 970 million
Kyats (3.23 million dollars) and over 1,400 staff, and bank
deposits amounted to over 47,000 million Kyats (156.67 million
dollars) up to January 1999.
</P>
<P>
There are 19 private banks in Myanmar now with the AWB, the
Yoma Bank and the May Flower Bank leading in domestic commercial
banking services.
</P>
<P>
Up to the end of 1998, nearly 60 branches had been opened
throughout the country to enhance the financial sector.
</P>
<P>
Private banks in the country have been allowed to operate again
since 1990, 27 years after all private banks in the country were
nationalized in 1963.
</P>
<P>
The private banks hold 42.3 percent of saving deposits of the
banking sector while their loans account for 44.9 percent of the
sector's loans to the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Private banks in the country are not allowed to conduct foreign
exchange transaction business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
