<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jamaican PM Calls for Debate on Banana Issue at Caribbean Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Jamaican Prime Minister Percival
Patterson said in Port-of-Spain Friday that the implications of
the recent World Trade Organization (WTO) decision about bananas
must be discussed at the Caribbean States Association's second
summit scheduled for next week in the Dominican Republic
</P>
<P>
A WTO panel ruled that the European Union (EU) banana import
rules violate free trade regulations. It also decided that the
United States can impose trade sanctions for 191.4 million U.S.
dollars to compensate for the loss each year.
</P>
<P>
Patterson, also president of the Caribbean Community (Caricom)
Foreign Negotiations Committee, said he has held talks with
authorities of the islands affected by the WTO decision. He added
that he is seeking solutions to improve the situation.
</P>
<P>
Saint Lucia Agriculture Minister Cassius Elias said he does not
think the Caribbean banana producing countries have lost their
interest in the trade war between the United States and the EU.
</P>
<P>
He said banana producers must not feel discouraged by the
regulation and should concentrate on reducing the high production
costs.
</P>
<P>
Other Caribbean leaders are also incensed over U.S. efforts to
get the WTO to revoke preferences given by some European countries
to former colonies in the region.
</P>
<P>
The United States is seeking penalties of more than 500 million
dollars on cashmere sweaters, Greek cheese and other imports from
the EU in retaliation for European regulations that discriminate
against bananas grown in Latin America by U.S. companies Chiquita
Brands International and Dole Foods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
