<DOCNO> XIE19990410.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: ABCs of Macao SAR Basic Law (21) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Following is Part 21 of a
question and answer series of the ABCs of the Basic Law of the
Macao Special Administrative Region (MSAR).
</P>
<P>
How should the independent judicial power of the Macao Special
Administrative Region be understood?
</P>
<P>
The judicial power is the power exclusively enjoyed by the
judicial organ in trying cases according to law and supervising
the enforcement of law.
</P>
<P>
Generally, as an important principle underlying the political
institutions, judicial independence exists in relation to the
executive power and legislative power.
</P>
<P>
It means that in trying cases, the judicial organ acts in
accordance with law and is free from any interference by the
executive organ or legislative organ. However, the independent
judicial power enjoyed by the MSAR as provided for in the Basic
Law is different from the principle of judicial independence in
the general sense of the term.
</P>
<P>
The "independent judicial power" in this context is not
intended to define its relations with the executive branch and the
legislative branch on a horizontal basis. Rather, it is intended
to stress that vertically, in terms of the relationship between
the Central Government and the MSAR, the judicial power of the
MSAR is not subject to the jurisdiction of the supreme judicial
organ of the country.
</P>
<P>
The affairs covered by its judicial power are entirely within
the scope of autonomy of the MSAR. It is precisely because of the
independent judicial power vested in it that the MSAR shall set up
a court of final adjudication and enjoy complete power of final
adjudication.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990410.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Almost 200,000 Thai Students Use Drugs: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Narcotics Control
Board (NCB) estimates that almost 200,000 students across the
country, or 1.4 percent of the student population, are addicted to
drugs, Jurin Laksanavisit, Minister of the Prime Minister's
Office, said.
</P>
<P>
Of the total 199,000 students using narcotics, 45.06 percent
are vocational students, 26.05 percent are from schools under the
General Education Department, 24.18 percent from schools under
National Primary Education Office, while 4.71 percent are
university students, Jurin said in remarks published by Saturday's
Nation newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Amphetamines top the list among young drug users at 78.5
percent, while inhalant drugs account for 2.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Payon Pansri, secretary-general of the NCB, said
drugs are most rampant among students in the central provinces
with the number of young drug addicts accounting for 35 percent of
the total. Bangkok and northern provinces ranked second, with 24
percent each, northeastern provinces accounted for 13 percent,
with southern provinces making up 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The NCB will join up with Assumption University in conducting a
survey about drug addition among students two months after schools
reopen in the next semester.
</P>
<P>
The agency will evaluate the success of anti-drug campaigns at
the end of the year and again over the next two years by
considering three indices: areas where drugs use has severely
increased or decreased; whether the number of young (non-student)
addicts has increased or decreased; and the number of students
addicted to drugs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
