<HEADLINE> Mexico, Canada Move Toward Strategic Alliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Mexico and Canada are marching
toward a strategic alliance, Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
During the welcome ceremony for visiting Canadian Prime
Minister Jean Chretien, Zedillo said he is satisfied with the
implementation of the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA),
which groups Mexico, Canada and the United States.
</P>
<P>
He highlighted the benefits incurred by the three countries
through NAFTA, saying that five years after signing the agreement,
trade between Mexico and Canada has increased 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Mexicans feel very proud of their relationship with Canada,
because it is based on mutual respect and friendship."
</P>
<P>
Zedillo said that Chretien's visit will strengthen the
constructive dialogue between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chretien said that relations with Mexico have
developed smoothly and he will discuss with President Zedillo new
directions to sustain good relations.
</P>
<P>
After the ceremony, the two leaders held private talks.
</P>
<P>
Mexico and Canada are to sign agreements on aviation, health,
environment, housing, science and technology during Chretien's
three-day visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
