<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Says no to IMF's Budget Deficit Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
trashed prescriptions of the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
calling for a bigger deficit spending this year as way of
stimulating economic growth, the Philippine Post newspaper Said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu as
saying that government will stick to the existing 68.4 billion
peso (1 U.S. dollar is equal to about 40 pesos) deficit program
which remains attainable.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that there is still a good chance for the
government to improve its revenue collection.
</P>
<P>
"I am very optimistic that the March collection of the Bureau
of Internal Revenue will be very good, to be improved further in
April which is the tax season," he said.
</P>
<P>
The visiting IMF mission was concerned that the Philippines
might not realize a positive growth unless the government spends
more to fuel important economic activities.
</P>
<P>
Under the standby IMF program, the country should grow by at
least 2.5 percent in terms of the gross national product and post
a two percent gross domestic production in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
