<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Backs U.N. Appeal to Resolve Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The Italian government voiced support
on Friday for an appeal by United Nations Secretary General Kofi
Annan urging Yugoslavia to halt military action in Kosovo and
withdraw its army and militia forces from the province.
</P>
<P>
In a long telephone conversation with Annan, Italian Prime
Minister Massimo D'Alema said he and his government are firmly
behind the appeal and hope Annan's words would be heeded and win
the support of the entire U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Annan called on Belgrade to end its "campaign of intimidation
and deportation" of civilians, allow the return of refugees and
the deployment of an international military force to ensure the
safety of these people and the arrival of humanitarian aid
shipments.
</P>
<P>
A communique issued by the premier's office said the Italian
government hopes these developments point to a way out of the
Kosovo crisis and will restore a leading role to the U.N. in the
search for a negotiated settlement leading to peace and stability
in the sensitive Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini said Italy
fully approved the initiative and urged the U.N. to take a
positive position. 
</P>
</TEXT>
