<HEADLINE> Mexico, Canada Sign Social Cooperation Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The Mexican and Canadian
governments signed a series of cooperation agreements Friday in
areas of environment, education and communications as part of
efforts to strengthen relations during Prime Minister Jean
Chretien's three-day official visit here.
</P>
<P>
The two governments "have built during the last decade a
relationship which grows closer and more dynamic every day, and
which encompasses a wide range of government activities," said the
1999 Mexico-Canada relation statement of objectives.
</P>
<P>
The geographical link between the two countries is "one of the
strong points of the relationship," which is creating a sense of
community within North America."
</P>
<P>
Among the accords signed Friday by the two nations is one
referring to satellite services aimed at regulating the
communication through fixed and mobile stations in the territories
of the two nations.
</P>
<P>
Another agreement signed Friday is one that modifies a previous
one on air transportation between the two countries, including new
regulations on air safety, charter flights and frequency.
</P>
<P>
A statement on sanitary cooperation was also made on the second
day of Chretien's official visit to Mexico. He is scheduled to
travel to the state of Puebla, east of Mexico City, on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The declaration states the commitment to cooperation activities
related to tobacco addiction, aging, drug abuse, epidemiological
surveillance and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The two governments signed a letter of intention on the
exchange of information about forest fires, creating joint
projects to support the forecast, detection, and control of forest
fires in Mexico. 
</P>
</TEXT>
