<DOCNO> XIE19990410.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Election Plans Finalized: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's General Election
Commission (KPU) Friday announced his 53-member team has completed
all preparations to facilitate the implementation of the June 7
poll.
</P>
<P>
Rudini rejected pessimistic comments from several political
analysts, who say the "sluggish" performance of the KPU may delay
the general election.
</P>
<P>
Analysts also fear that recent bloody clashes in many region
may disrupt the election.
</P>
<P>
But Rudini said the KPU has done its best and ultimately the
fate of the election is in God's hands.
</P>
<P>
"Our works refer to the June 7 general election and the
preparations have now been completed. But as human beings, we can
only make the efforts, God will make the decision (on whether the
election will be delayed or not)," Rudini said.
</P>
<P>
Rudini said the election regulations issued by the KPU include
campaign rules, monitoring activities, voter registration
requirements, and numerous other matters.
</P>
<P>
He said the matter of ballots has also been agreed upon. On
Tuesday, nine printing companies with security certificates from
the National Intelligence Agency will commence printing the
ballots.
</P>
<P>
"The security of the ballot printing is vital, because it
directly relates to the credibility of the June general election.
The printing companies cannot print more than they have been
ordered to. Not even one ballot more," he said.
</P>
<P>
The ballots will be ready in the capitals of all Indonesian
provinces on May 10, Rudini said.
</P>
<P>
The total general election budget is 1.3 trillion rupiah (about
150 million U.S. dollars), including 150 million rupiah for each
party, Rudini was quoted by the Indonesian Observer Saturday as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Voter registration commenced on April 5 and will close on May
5. The official campaign period begins on May 19 and will conclude
on June 4.
</P>
<P>
On June 7, voter are scheduled to elect 462 members of the
House of Representatives (DPR), who will join 38 appointees from
the Indonesian National Armed Forces.
</P>
<P>
The 500 House members will later this year meet with 135
delegates from regions and 65 delegates from various groups to
form the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR).
</P>
<P>
The MPR will convene in November to elect the next president
and vice president.
</P>
<P>
After the June election, parties with the majority of votes in
each respective province and district, will name their cadres who
will sit in provincial and district legislative assemblies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
