<HEADLINE> Political Solution to Be Sought for Kosovo: French FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Allied military actions were needed
in Kosovo but sooner or later a political solution will be sought,
said French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine who arrived here
Friday for a one-day visit at the invitation of his Bulgarian
counterpart Nadezhda Mihailova.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference following his meeting with Mihailova,
Vedrine said Bulgaria and France have similar positions on the
Kosovo crisis. Both sides agree that people who were chased away,
traumatized and maltreated should not be driven away from their
homes a second time, he said, adding that France would provide aid.
</P>
<P>
On the future of the region, Vedrine said dialogue between
Bulgaria and France on security and stability in the Balkans will
continue.
</P>
<P>
Mihailova briefed Vedrine on Sofia's program to limit the
fallout on Bulgaria from the war in Kosovo, and called on France
to support and provide specific aid in infrastructure projects and
attracting foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine promised that the Paris Club will review the situation
resulting from the Kosovo crisis at its next session.
</P>
<P>
France has suggested that the European Union (EU) review its
relations with Yugoslavia's neighbors in order to accelerate a
speedier EU integration, Vedrine said.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Vedrine met with Bulgarian President Peter
Stoyanov on the Kosovo crisis and the refugees issue. They agreed
that NATO military operations were inevitable and legitimate, but
the two were also considering a future political solution, Vedrine
said after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine reiterated France's desire to strengthen political
dialogue with Bulgaria. "We want to further develop bilateral
relations in the political, economic and cultural field," he said.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine also met with Bulgarian Prime Minister Ivan Kostov and
leaders of the parliamentary Committee on Foreign and Integration
Policy.
</P>
<P>
The French foreign minister praised Bulgaria's stand on the
Kosovo crisis and committed himself to presenting before the EU
General Affairs Council Bulgaria's program to reduce the negative
effects of the Kosovo crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
