<HEADLINE> Venezuelan Oil Price Closes Slightly Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The average price of Venezuelan
crude during the week ending Friday was 12.95 U.S. dollars per
barrel, nine cents below the average price last week, the Energy
and Mines Ministry (MEM) announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
This slight drop leaves the average price for the year at 9.88
dollars per barrel, below the 10.63 dollars in 1998, and far below
the 1997 average of 16.32 dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
The MEM said the drop corresponds to "a correction in the
market after a strong rise in the previous weeks and to the
normalization of operations in United States refineries."
</P>
<P>
The oil prices have strengthened since the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) members and independent
producers decided in March to reduce the supply and force the main
consuming nations to use their inventories.
</P>
<P>
Oil makes up 70 percent of Venezuelan exports and provides more
than 50 percent of the income for its national budget.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said that for every dollar the oil price goes
up or down, Venezuela's treasury earns or loses about one billion
dollars a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
