<HEADLINE> North China City Clamps Down On Exhaust Emissions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The government of Taiyuan,
capital of Shanxi Province, has issued a regulation for the
control of motor vehicle emissions.
</P>
<P>
An official with local environment protection bureau said that
as of July 1, all the city's gas stations will stop sale of leaded
gasoline to make sure that lead-free gasoline is being used.
</P>
<P>
"The city is suffering from severe air pollution, which is
partly a result of motor vehicle emissions," he said, adding that
strict standards on emission control are badly needed.
</P>
<P>
All motor vehicles being sold or operating within the city have
to have emission control examinations, according to the regulation.
Any vehicles sold or driven that exceed exhaust standards will be
prohibited from being used.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the city will get rid of thousands of over
ten year old vehicles that cause pollution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
