<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Okays '99 Investment Priorities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' Board of
Investments has endorsed the 1999 Investment Priorities Plan (IPP)
without objections, Manila Standard newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The IPP is an annual listing of government's preferred areas of
economic activity that are eligible for fiscal incentives such as
duty-free importation of equipment.
</P>
<P>
Board of Investments Executive Director Elmer Hernandez was
quoted by the newspaper as saying that the 1999 IPP aims to direct
investments in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
Other objectives of the 1999 IPP are: create employment and
reduce the cost of living, increase agricultural productivity
through modernization and support the development of small and
medium enterprises, Hernandez said.
</P>
<P>
Unlike the previous IPPs, he noted, the 1999 IPP integrates the
priority activity of each region, which means some industries may
be eligible for incentives in one region but may not be eligible
for incentives in other regions.
</P>
<P>
The inclusion of an industry is based on whether or not the
industry will be profitable based on such measures as the domestic
resource cost, the revealed comparative advantage, economic
internal rate of return and market, technical and financial
analysis, he said.
</P>
<P>
Other factors that the IPP take into account are the industry's
linkages with upstream and downstream projects and its
infrastructure requirements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990410.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
