<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Exploration Goes With Environmental Protection In Tarim Basin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Many overseas and domestic
environmentalists worried about the environment at the Tarim Basin
in far northwest Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region when large-scale
oil exploration began there in 1989.
</P>
<P>
After 10 years of development, however, the local environment
has been improving rather than deteriorating thanks to the efforts
of the Tarim Basin Oil Exploration and Development Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
According to Wang Daixuan, an official in charge of
environmental protection with the headquarters, 410 million yuan,
or 2 percent of the total investment at the site, has been spent
on environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Now, eight oil fields that are in production are free from oil
pollution and 40 stations have been established to monitor air and
water quality in the oil fields.
</P>
<P>
Also, 10 million yuan has been invested for the trial
construction of an artificial oasis in this desert land, with
plants and grasses that grow well in the arid sand-dunes covered
region.
</P>
<P>
Some 230,000 trees and grasses covering an area of 150,000
square meters were planted around oil exploration areas in the
past decade.
</P>
<P>
Located in the hinterland of the Eurasian continent, 60 percent
of the Tarim Basin is covered by the 324,000-square-kilometer
Taklimakan Desert, the world's second largest floating desert.
</P>
<P>
Known as the "Sea of Death," the desert's annual precipitation
is only 50 millimeters, and sandstorms hit the area every four
days on average.
</P>
<P>
The Tarim Basin has proven oil and gas reserves of 19.1 billion
tons and is expected to become a giant energy base in northwest
China in the next century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990410.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
