<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Announces Ethics Commission Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAUSANNE, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The International Olympic
Committee (IOC) president announced the individuals selected to be
members of the IOC Ethics Commission, the new commission charged
with providing guidance on how the IOC operates in accordance with
the best practice of international governance.
</P>
<P>
Formerly approved at the 108th Session in March, the Ethics
Commission will be responsible for developing a framework of
principles and rules, and to ensure their adoption. It will look
at all issues in contravention of these principles and rules in
order to make recommendations to the Executive Board of the IOC.
The Commission will immediately address the responsibilities of
the IOC, including the candidature and selection process of host
cities for the Olympic Games as well as the organization and
staging of the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
The Ethics Commission is composed of eight individuals, three
of whom are IOC members and five prominent individuals known for
their independence of spirit, their competency and their
international reputation. The three IOC members include Judge Keba
Mbaye of Senegal, Kevan Gosper of Australia and Chiharu Igaya of
Japan.
</P>
<P>
Members from outside the IOC include former United States
Senator Howard Baker, former President of the French Constitution
Court and Senator Robert Badinter of France, former United Nations
Secretary General Javier Perez de Cuellar of Peru, former Swiss
President Kurt Furgler of Switzerland and Olympic athlete
Charmagne Crooks of Canada. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
