<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BSkyB/Man United Deal Blocked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The Department of Trade and
Industry of Britain ruled on Friday to block the takeover deal by
the BSkyB of the leading English soccer club Manchester United Plc.
</P>
<P>
Trade Secretary Stephen Byers said that the one billion dollar
deal "may be expected to operate against the public interest and
that it should be prohibited".
</P>
<P>
The 623 million pound (999.2 million U.S. dollars) bid by BSkyB,
40 percent owned by Rupert Murdoch's News Corp, was referred to
Britain's Monopolies and Mergers Commission (MMC) last October.
The MMC presented its report to Byers last month and the minister
said he had accepted its findings.
</P>
<P>
"The MMC's findings are based mainly on competition grounds,
where they concluded that the merger would adversely affect
competition between broadcasters," Byers said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"But they also examined wider public interest issues,
concluding that the merger would damage the quality of British
football," he added.
</P>
<P>
The planned deal would have brought together the nation's
leading pay TV broadcaster and the biggest and most successful
English soccer club. BSkyB has live TV rights to premier league
matches under a contract which runs until 2001.
</P>
<P>
The decision was immediately greeted by Manchester United
supporters opposed to the takeover. Shares in the club dived on
the London Stock Exchange in reaction to the news. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
