<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schroeder to Be Elected SPD Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The German Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder is due to be formally confirmed as chairman of the
ruling Social Democratic Party (SPD) at the party's special
congress scheduled for next Monday.
</P>
<P>
The convention in Bonn will be attended by 450 delegates,
representing 775,000 members of the biggest political party in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
The one-day congress is expected to easily and unopposedly
elect Schroeder to head the SPD, and to approve Germany's role in
NATO operations against Yugoslavia, party officials said.
</P>
<P>
"I expect the German government and its policy to be
strengthened by the SPD party congress," Defense Minister Rudolf
Scharping said Friday, adding that about 70 percent of the party
members backed the government's policy in Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder, holding the control over the SPD since the
surprising resignation of Oscar Lafonaine both as party chairman
and Finance Minister in March, has won support of the exacutive
circle.
</P>
<P>
And, the traditional wingers in the SPD following Lafontaine,
who have been strongly against the NATO strikes, are reportedly
toning down a counter-resolution that doest not directly demand
halt to NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
The main demand of the party traditionalists will be that the
United Nations, not NATO, should secure peace in Kosovo, the
Frankfurt Allgemeine newspaper said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990410.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn Rejects Ground Troops for Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 9 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder
and Defense Minister Rudolf Scharping Friday clearly rejected
sending NATO ground combat forces to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"The German government sees no reason to change its strategy.
We have made it clear that we do not want to deploy ground
troops," Schroeder said in an interview by the German RTL
television.
</P>
<P>
Sending ground forces is not in Bonn's agenda, Defense Minister
Rudolf Scharping said.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer told the
ZDF television that he could not decide if deployment of ground
troops was unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
"I do not know, I cannot make this decision given the current
situation," Fischer said.
</P>
<P>
The interview did not mean any shift toward backing ground
troops, a Foreign Ministry spokesman said Friday.
</P>
<P>
A poll by Germany's N-TV channel showed that 60 percent of
those surveyed were opposed to deploying ground forces. And, they
also firmly said "no" against the possibility that German forces
take part in the ground campaigns outside Germany.
</P>
<P>
"The red line must not be crossed," former Defense Minister
Volker Ruehe of the opposition Christian Democratic Union (CDU)
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
