<DOCNO> XIE19990410.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Markets Close Higher On Back Of Rates Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 9 (Xinhua) -- European stock markets closed
higher Friday after a larger than expected cut in euro zone
interest rates by the European Central Bank (ECB).
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 closed 0.54 percent, or 34.9 points, higher
at 6472.8, just shy of its record closing high set Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the session, the index had breached the
psychologically significant 6500 barrier for the first time,
marking its third intraday high of the week.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say investors are now focusing on the seriousness of
possible Russian involvement in the Yugoslav crisis.
</P>
<P>
"We've had a very strong week, and now it's time to take a
breather to see where things are going," said a London trader.
</P>
<P>
German's Xetra DAX closed at 5133.92, up 66.16 points, on hopes
that the interest rates cut by the ECB will stimulate the German
economy.
</P>
<P>
However, the market lost some of its optimism on reports that
Russia was targeting missiles at some European countries as a
result of the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
"This news broke the market's impetus," a trader said. "The
threat seems serious and we really don't know what to expect," he
added.
</P>
<P>
French share prices closed higher but off earlier highs. The
Cac 40 index finished up 32.44 points at 4363.14.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
